The Higgs boson is analyzed
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused some stir last summer, and for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted by the standard model - our best or "least wrong" explanation of nature and the behavior of matter - but has not yet been empirically observed.
But for physicists, it is not yet completely certain that it is really Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
Moreover, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but there is still no data to be absolutely sure about it.
Let’s still assume that it’s actually Higgs, as there seems to be only a slight risk of being deceived, and let’s look at what it’s about.
There is an inevitable law in this world that prevents two objects from being in the same place at the same time.
It’s not possible to violate this rule – and don’t try too hard as you’re going to hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a truly strange world, it turns out that such a law also applies to it: the Pauli principle of exclusion, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quantum state", whereby this "state" consists largely of some of its properties.
Based on this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens, who are called Fermione and kindly obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosons move, an evil gang of anarchists to whom nothing is sacred - certainly not this principle, which means that they can in fact be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons, according to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley laboratories (which by the way is absolutely amazing) are divided into two groups: the mesons that we will not treat here and the "force particles" through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
But it must be emphasized here that these bosons are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or "particle of light", which is the "messenger" of electromagnetic force.
If a particle accelerates with an electrical charge or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is "disrupted" exactly at this location, much like a pebble that has been thrown into a pond.
This "disturbance" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force".
More stable field
The same goes for the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, needs to be "disrupted" in order for this boson to appear.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, a little like a frozen pond, whose surface could only be shattered by a very large rock.
That’s why a huge particle accelerator like CERN – the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! – is needed to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others don’t – for example, a sheet of paper would never hold on to the refrigerator by itself.
And equally, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do have a mass, while the others (as, by the way, the photon) do not have a mass.
For what can all these researches be "good," Mrs Plamondon asks?
For science, they serve to verify the Standard Model (SM), and they also allow physicists to accurately examine any deviations between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who eagerly hope that such deviations will be found, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and stuff some holes in the model.
It must be said that the latter still has major shortcomings, as it does not provide an explanation for gravity (ups!) and dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter in the universe (ups!).
However, such deviations have not yet been found at CERN.
Consequences
The impact of these researches on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there are none.
By the way, in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle – who worked in the Bell Labs where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first ones were pulsed) in 1962 – has already told us that the laser was initially seen more as a “laboratory game.”
Just imagine...
In addition, applications can also result from all the instruments that surround the research.
For example, in 1969, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work in optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor now serves all digital cameras worldwide as an "eye" and earned it the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it does mean that you really can never know...
Palliative care - the best way to die... <0x7C> Le Devoir
With its committee on “Death in Dignity,” Quebec has recently discussed the delicate question of the end of life.
The debate has to be resumed shortly, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, there is still much to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to take a closer look at this.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that ate him had left him a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I managed seven years," he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
"However, it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for it," he says.
The disease does its job: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating for himself.
Sitting at the table before a tasty lunch, he resignedly agrees to get help with eating.
Boldly, he even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medications, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is that you cure my diarrhea because it is humiliating," he said.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"In the course of our lives, we learn that a man is peeing standing," says Pierre Brodeur, psychologist at Victor-Gadbois home.
Returning to childhood is an unacceptable humiliation for certain people.
"It depends on the person's ability to take a step backwards," he notes.
According to several people working in palliative care, major events take place in the midst of these backlashes.
The patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home are all suffering from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, the doctors and nurses who take care of them no longer overwhelm them with so-called "healing" care.
For Ms. A., 89 years old, the worst fear is to die “consciously and through suffocation”.
But because of the disease, I really got to know my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I don't have any wishes in life anymore," she says before accepting that you put on a mask to help her breathe.
In the next few days, she expects a last visit from her son, who comes from Italy.
In the Victor-Gadbois home, a group of volunteers offer personal care and assistance with food intake.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make dying more enjoyable.
In Quebec, a bed for palliative care is available for 11,700 residents.
That is very little if you consider that we will all die one day.
Here life is continued under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors at the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
Depending on your wishes, you can give the dying person a mouth care with brandy or Pepsi.
Diabetics no longer need to control their blood sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died in the course of the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help relatives and patients alike," says nursing director Nathalie Savard.
In the Victor-Gadbois home, there is no day like the other.
In addition to a 93-year-old man who enjoys the last family gathering in the yard and is well supported by his pillows while pushing on in his honor, a young man of 36 years, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children, dies tragically after trying everything to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds have always been occupied with cancer patients under the age of 45," says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home come from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care designed to alleviate the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the final stage of their lives, either at home, in a hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois Home and the Society for Home Palliative Care in the Greater Montreal area, specialize more or less exclusively in caring for cancer patients.
It is precisely this great inadequacy in Quebec’s health care that causes several palliative care specialists to look forward to passing a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide with concern.
Since the month of October, a manifesto has been in circulation, signed by prominent palliative care personalities such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec’s health care system is not powerful enough to ensure that everyone has the right to high-quality palliative care before accepting to switch to euthanasia.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room for 14 days with great pain without any action taken to relieve her.
I fear that patients will die only because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients bitterly until the last day despite the worst prognoses.
Hélène Richard’s chances of survival were already minimal when she discontinued difficult chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop the treatment, she replied that she regretted that I gave up the fight, she told me.
She told me I was in the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the nurses that it has not granted that wish after their pain has been alleviated by a palliative care team.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care is not omnipotent in pain treatment.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care of the Society of Home Palliative Care of the Greater Montreal area, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
Thus, at the very end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which results in either sporadically or permanently sleeping the patient until the time of his death.
We can no longer pretend that we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not alleviated, all say the same phrase, "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean, “I want you to put me to sleep,” but “I want my pain to be alleviated.”
