After Bitcoin’s price peaked at $30 in June 2011, it fell to $2 five months later, before recovering to around $10 today (the prices are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to the world trade of real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes Bitcoin as “the virtual currency with the greatest success,” “competing with the dollar or the euro,” and “similar to conventional currencies.”
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies such as the “credits” that are used to advance in a video game that can be won or bought (and sometimes exchanged back) by playing games.
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, the trade is controlled and processed by a central authority every time.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously custodians of the accounting book, auditors, money issuers, as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses in the form of an email.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of data related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can check the authenticity of the transaction.
Using the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the traded Bitcoins are present in the public account accounts account spread throughout the network.
The decisive step is to enter this new transaction into this book.
This is done through a mathematical task that is started on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of interim central banker, having the privilege of adding that additional line.
It is a fragmentation of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unique electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole is "hacked".
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes can effortlessly check if it is the right one.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to cheat twice very quickly (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain unlinked, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the problem will receive 50 Bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
The bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but divisible to one hundred millionth, leaving some room for manoeuvre...
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with each improvement in computing power.
The life of the network has already had highs and lows.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin have been attacked and the Bitcoin deposits stolen.
“The vulnerability used does not concern the actual protocol,” assures Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a company for real money payments and uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering using this anonymous service.
However, cash also has these shortcomings.
Important actors such as Wikipedia refuse to make donations of this kind.
They are accepted by others like the blogging platform WordPress.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the accounting book and showed that almost 80% of bitcoins are out of circulation.
In November, a "mega final sale" was launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, who works for the company Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book about this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transactional network.
His Paytunia system is equivalent to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate the transactions, which are cheaper as a result.
In addition, the owner manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented at the dealers, and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
All you have to do is provide an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, says Pierre Noizat, who assures him that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend of rethinking hierarchical systems in favour of more horizontal systems.
“It will take some time for Bitcoin to prevail, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
The ECB’s report also provides for a reassessment of the various risks that are now regarded as high risks in the event of the currency’s success.
