A constitution with the crushing rod in Egypt
This is a new poker game by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever in terms of the Constitutional Declaration, which temporarily grants it unlimited powers, it has decided to put everything on a map.
To everyone’s surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would pass its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had granted this plenary two additional months to complete its work.
Egypt has been relying on a preliminary, repeatedly amended text for almost two years now, which weakens institutional stability and leads to a legal mess.
This new initiative has only resulted in an even stronger division of the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his “autocratic delirium” by continuing to “break his word” and “piss the law at its feet”.
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time, forcing the brothers to renounce their plan to explain the text section by section to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to regain his public and democratic legitimacy as the protest rages across the country.
According to confirmations in an interview with the American weekly Time, Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favour.
Especially since the Egyptian people are given an ultimatum with this recourse to an hasty vote: "Either you vote for my draft or I retain unlimited power of attorney", the latter should supposedly end after the adoption of the Constitution.
Eighty-five mostly Islamist members of this Constituent Assembly passed the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of liberals have not responded to the call.
Shortly before the Declaration of the Constitution in mid-November, they turned their backs because they felt that they were unable to express their views.
Representatives of human rights organizations, religious minorities or civil society have acted alike.
In order to achieve the quorum, 11 persons, deputy members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that the articles were mostly adopted unanimously.
By the way, the commentators found it entertaining that the only difference of opinion of the day ... was expressed in the time of prayer, as some members of the board felt that the pendulum clock of the Constituent Assembly did not go exactly.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Finally, Article 2, which attracted all attention, remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, had hoped to replace "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made stricter application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their goodwill and their respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
Hypocrisy is the answer of the liberals, who see this as a mere propaganda attack.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place via other articles.
In particular, they have in mind Article 220, which grants the University of Al-Azhar an advisory function, in particular with regard to the verification of conformity with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying, as "people being asked to comment have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy whatsoever.
You can see here the first signs of a theocracy."
The fears of the liberals are also fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be far less moderate than the current rector.
“At the moment, there is no concrete religious commitment.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulemas, but academics who have been partly trained in the French system,” says Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He admits, however, that "there may be ambiguity with regard to Article 220, since the terms used are borrowed from religious vocabulary.
It refers here in particular to the "Fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence, note].
And in the future, the question could be raised to what extent civil judges are competent to decide on it."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is heavily criticised for the far-reaching powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of controversy: the powers of the army.
In line with the wishes of the military, the review of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Likewise, there will be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as the associations for the defence of human rights have demanded.
The latter also share their fears regarding the text, which they consider to be a threat to freedom.
The crime of blasphemy is maintained, and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Moreover, no article refers to the protection of women, underlines Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In her opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists await sacred sites, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the glory of biblical truths, modern comfort and untouched nature.
AIF gives you the five main reasons for visiting Israel.
Prostrate before the holy places
Visit the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river receive God’s blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the conversion of water into wine at a wedding feast, the walking on the water, the quenching of the sea storm and the fishing.
This is where Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
Most of the temples are located in Jerusalem.
Believers take the Way of the Passion or the Way of the Cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path begins at the Roman fortress Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the church of the tomb on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion site, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, in the Christian view, is the navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of humanity.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands at the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
Jerusalem is also home to the most sacred place of the Jews - the Lament Wall, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave notes with wishes, which then come true.
Take a trip uphill
The ruins of the fortress Massada form the remains of the secret hiding place from enemies that Herod the Great had built for his family in A.D. 25.
They lie on a rock face in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only mountaineers can reach the ruins on their own.
Everyone else brings an aerial cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at 1600 to 2040 meters altitude is the famous ski resort Hermon, which attracts countless tourists during the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there by shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods lived on the summit.
Visit unique museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
Not all of them can be visited on a single trip.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be visited.
Among them is the Israel Museum near the Knesset (Parliament).
There, ancient Qumran manuscripts or scrolls from the Dead Sea found in caves in the Judean Desert are preserved, as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
It exhibits the collection of works by the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Acre you can visit the museum in Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of ancient Turkish baths with sculptures of the then visitors and bath attendants.
In Caesarea, you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures by Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are generally refused.
The fifth museum, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most poignant section is the Children’s Monument, built in memory of the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
When entering the room, there is total darkness.
Stars sparkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Doing something for health
The three most important recreational areas of Israel are on the shores of the Mediterranean, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
At each of the three places there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Surprisingly, the Red Sea is also bathed in the winter months, as the water temperature does not drop below 21 °C and the air warms to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and it is bathed all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea at 417 meters below sea level is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise-blue water has a high salt content and therefore carries even non-swimmers easily on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural brine) and curative mud, as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to soothe stressed nerves.
Touching the secrets of antiquity
These secrets lie in the old town of Tel Aviv, the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city ran the famous sea route that connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets named after the zodiac signs.
Legend has it that Fortuna is held by anyone who touches the walls in the alley with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa you can meet newlywed couples from all over Israel and even other countries at photo appointments.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theatre and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre now offers evening concerts and operas.
Checklist for tourists
If you’re going to Israel, don’t worry about your poor English skills: About 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the trip should not be taken in euros, but in dollars, which can easily be exchanged in shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you usually get ahead by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a highway and in Haifa the only subway line in the country with six stations connecting the lower city with the upper city.
In fact, it is an underground funicular.
A trip within the city costs 6 shekels regardless of the means of transport, which is enough including transfers for a trip of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is observed in Israel on Saturdays.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport is at rest.
On Sunday morning, the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and restaurants, only kosher food is served, excluding pork, seafood, dandruff-free fish and food that includes both dairy and meat products.
Instead, you have the choice between different dishes of mutton and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls of pureed beans and peas (falafel), as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
For this there are many well-nourished cats who stroll cosily and undisturbed through the streets.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of cars parked.
The cats like busy places and do not say no to treats.
Depending on the brand, a rental car costs from $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
The insurance costs an additional $15 per day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels per day.
Museum tickets cost an average of 30 shekels.
In numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most of the adventurers and recreational seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the United States and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118,8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Land, an increase of 51% compared to the 2010 comparison period, before the lifting of the visa requirement on February 9, 2011.
"The big and powerful" leads to Moscow: migrants save money for language
While MPs and civil rights activists are discussing the benefits of the law on mandatory language tests for migrants, criminals are already trading with fake certificates.
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, Saint Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are the citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to support the families left in the home.
On December 1st, a law came into force requiring every migrant worker to take a test that certifies knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this rule only applies to migrants who want to work in the services sector, in the municipal housing sector and in the retail sector.
However, according to the Federal Migration Authority, the tests will become mandatory for all guest workers in the future.
In doing so, you need to take not only language tests, but also tests into Russian history and the basics of legislation.
Language skills must be demonstrated for both obtaining and renewing the work permit.
Exceptions only apply to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Also exempt from this law are persons who received their training certificates and diplomas before the disintegration of the USSR in 1991.
Meaning, problem and protection of rights
The entirety of the examination bodies will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for the Russian Language, the Russian University of International Friendship, the Moscow State University, the Saint Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take the tests in all cities; already more than 160 corresponding centers have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
Civil rights activists, on the other hand, asked the following question several times before the law came into force in the press: What does the whole thing actually bring?
What changes does the requirement to demonstrate language skills bring, both for the Russians and for the guest workers?
Above all, according to spokespersons from the Migration Agency, the aim is to reduce the number of forced labourers.
"Many are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers," said Viktor Sebelev, head of the Federal Migration Agency in Tajikistan.
However, your rights must be protected before you leave.
Only an organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants with no occupation, education, language skills and medical examination are faced with problems.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with malicious intentions who, on the pretext of help, will put him in a dark, narrow barracks, where he will endure with dozens of his like months without food and documents and work 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our immigrants.
"At home, you will be promised the one, and on arrival you will be cheated, your passports will be taken and you will not receive the promised salary," confirmed the head of the Tajik Migration Agency's main labour migration department, Tolib Schwaripov.
Don't scold me, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to make money in Russia admit that they not only do not speak the language of the target country, but can hardly express themselves in their own language in writing.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: few Turkmens, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford even a reasonable primary education.
Because in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school supplies.
As teenagers, these children immediately seize the first opportunity to make money.
"It's difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Civil rights activists emphasize the following important aspect of the law.
Only immigrants with legal status are required to take the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, the majority of the guest workers continue to be illegally in Russia.
"Welcome" or "Access banned for unauthorized persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, linguistic difficulties.
In addition, the legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The staff of the Russian police know that our documents are mostly forged and we are not registered, and then cases of blackmail arise.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," Tajik Umed Hushkadamov told journalists.
"Just don't shy away from the cost of fake papers"
As early as the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the migrant’s registration documents could be counterfeit.
Some fake certificates attesting to the completion of the language test have already been seized by employees of the Federal Migration Authority.
The fake papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive this in vain: every migrant who hoped to be able to spare the tests, paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: it costs a worker migrant three thousand rubles.
The fact that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption, so that the certificates cannot be simply purchased, both officials and civil rights officials agree.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test for the first time that they will be given time for a basic language course.
In addition, newcomers without language skills are offered jobs in areas where there is no need for active communication with people.
Interior Ministry Ignores Illegal Arms Market
Proportion of legal weapons in crime extremely low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior plans to tighten the arms law for private arms owners.
The authorities are responding to the recent events: wounded in shootings at weddings and seven dead in the assassination of Moscow lawyer Dmitry Winogradov.
The police want to ban the carrying of non-lethal weapons in public and raise the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21.
The proposal has been supported by the chairman of the Duma Committee on Security and Combating Corruption, Irina Yarovaja, and promised that the amendments to the Arms Act will be presented to the Duma shortly.
Not everyone is satisfied with the fact that the Russian authorities want to tackle the problems by "attracting the screws".
An open letter has been published on the Internet, whose authors - representatives of various arms associations - are demanding from the authorities to refrain from "sinless tightening".
The percentage of crimes with registered weapons is very low, said the criminal justice officer, Vasily Lesnikov, the Russian service of the BBC.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, 142 crimes involving the use of registered weapons were committed in the course of six months in 2012, while for the same period a total of 1,168 thousand offences were recorded.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that tightening the law for private gun owners will not prevent criminals from making use of the black market.
Currently, according to the authors, you can find every possible weapon in Moscow for little money.
Meanwhile, the Interior Ministry stresses that the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The weapons enter the black market via several channels.
There are five such main channels, says a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who served in the Ministry of Education and General Staff for ten years.
Screenshot of a website accepting gun orders
The first channel is the army or military, i.e. weapons stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," Baranez said.
On the second channel, illegal weapons are stolen by criminals.
Baranez explains that these include weapons stolen from both the police armory and directly from law enforcement personnel.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons warehouses.
In many military camps, there were frequent explosions.
"There is evidence that in some cases it was arson to cover up the lack of weapons," the former military official said.
According to Baranez, arms manufacturers are also making a contribution to the black market.
"Today, there are countless private arms factories that are not able to withstand international competition and therefore discard the weapons under their hands on the black market, for example in Moscow," the expert reports.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Many guns and rifles come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a separate, sometimes artisanal production, as well as a mafia that organizes the smuggling," the former military official explains.
Where did the weapons come from?
Experts calculated the proportion of each of the five channels in the supply of illegal weapons to the black market.
In 2011, a report was prepared by the Center for Problem Analysis and State Administration.
The experts analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, Criminological Literature and publicly available data on weapons portals.
The majority of illegal weapons, according to the investigators, come from the army and the law enforcement authorities.
Half of all weapons on the black market were brought there by “the guilt of those responsible for their work with weapons,” the report said.
According to the researchers, 17% of weapons come from conflict areas, 14% from theft in the production of weapons, and 5% from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant at an arms store, who does not want to be named, assures that weapons found in illegal excavations have long since been bought by no one, as they are outdated.
According to him, it is more common for merchants to get supplies in an arms warehouse.
A weapon, such as a type TT gun, is purchased from an ensign.
The weapon is displayed and handed over through the fence.
"The dealer brings the gun to the city and sells it there for 900 euros each with two magazines," he says.
“Of course, the police are aware of everything and, therefore, if they cannot comply with the crime detection plan, they periodically carry out check purchases from dealers who offer illegal weapons,” the sales advisor adds.
"Like the luxury store"
Buyers and sellers most often find each other through acquaintances.
I had been looking at websites and blogs when someone noticed me and suggested I come to the station "Begovaya" where a person would wait for me to take me to a certain place where we could then negotiate the price.
The price of the gun I learned only there
