In recent days, there have been massive protests across the U.S. against low wages at Walmart stores and restaurants of popular fast food chains such as Mc Donald’s, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendy’s, and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
No one can predict whether the protests will continue to swell or if they will soon run out of air again.
The protests are supported by trade unions and several left-wing non-profit organizations.
In addition to raising the modest wages of ordinary Walmart and fast food workers, the organizers of the protests are pursuing the goal of establishing unions.
So far, this sector of the economy has hardly been organised in the trade unions.
46 cents a year?
The protests began last week after Thanksgiving, the so-called Black Friday, which saw sales in the United States attracting millions of customers, sometimes leading to handcuffs.
On that day, some Walmart employees, of whom there are 2.2 million worldwide, laid down their work and, along with trade unions and left-wing activists, stalled branches of the chain whose target group are low- and middle-income people.
Walmart sells all products, from diapers to hunting rifles and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
The goods in the Walmart stores are on average between 8 and 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
That’s why many of the low-paid Walmart employees buy only at their own workplace.
The prices and product range made Walmart one of the largest companies in the United States.
According to critics, Walmart can often sell the goods so cheaply only because the employees are poorly paid.
The latter also complain about difficult working conditions, for example missing forklifts or hand scanners.
Participants in the Black Friday protests called for wage increases and expressed their anger at the fact that the contribution to in-house health insurance had risen from $30 to $100 a month.
A typical Walmart employee earning $9.5 an hour could not afford this increase, they said.
Researchers from the California University in Berkeley prove that if the company increased the average wage to $12 an hour, it would cost Walmart $3.2 billion.
That’s about 1.1% more than they are now donating for wages.
If Walmart were to transfer the wage increases entirely to customers, each purchase would cost them only 46 cents more in the future.
For them, that would be an additional expense of just $12.39 per year compared to today.
Proponents of Walmart are pleased to note that there were protests in only nine states and that these caused no losses to the company.
Black Friday lasted in its store from 8 a.m. on Thursday to midnight the next day, and during that period, Walmart sold about 5,000 items per second.
In total, Walmart cash registers carried out almost 100 million transactions on Black Friday.
The company’s spokesman, Dan Fogelman, claimed in an interview on the website of the left-wing Huffington Post that a total of “less than five” Walmart employees stopped working and the protest campaign was merely “another PR trick” by the union that organized the protests.
"Free cash!"
The protests continued this week in New York, where their target was not Walmart stores (which are not desirable in this advanced city and are therefore so far inexisting), but McDonald's and other inexpensive restaurants.
McDonald's says the company sells billions of servings, and yet they don't grant you sick days, and you're not being paid for your honest work!
Jumaane Williams, Member of the New York City Council
Currently, the minimum wage according to federal and New York legislation is $7.25 an hour.
In fast-food restaurants, the minimum wage is gradually raised, but not too strongly, and on average, their simple New York employees are getting $8.90 an hour.
No one deserves less than her in this expensive city.
How it is possible to live in New York with so little money is incomprehensible to me.
There was a time when nearly a quarter of all American youth were behind the counter at McDonald’s after school, but the youth were still living with their parents.
Hardly anyone saw it as the main source of income or planned to stay there longer.
Now, in interviews with McDonald’s employees, I constantly meet people who complain that they have to live with that salary and sometimes even feed their children.
On the other hand, there is a comment in the Wall Street Journal forum whose author notes that it is irresponsible to have children if you do not know how to feed them.
Participants in the protests, which began at 6:30 a.m. in front of the McDonald’s on 40th Street and Madison Avenue on Thursday, demanded that fast-food restaurant cashiers and chefs receive a minimum wage of $15 an hour, more than doubling the current minimum wage.
They continued to call for the formation of trade unions in the fast food industry.
The U.S. law prohibits corporate governance from standing in the way of this goal and admonishing or dismissing union members.
On the other hand, corporate governance does not make it easy for them.
However, the establishment of trade unions in the fast food industry is also difficult for objective reasons.
The main reason is the high staff turnover.
Dissatisfied
There were loud protests that day in front of many other fast food restaurants in Manhattan.
The highlight of the protests was a meeting at noon in front of the McDonald's in Times Square, where some local Democrats spoke, including City Councilman Jumaane Williams, who said, "McDonald's says it sells billions of servings, and yet they don't grant you sick days, and you're not being paid for your honest work!"
The protesters were also supported by other prominent New York Democrats, for example, mayoral candidate Bill De Blasio, who said that "we should work together to support the fast-food employees so that they can receive a fair wage and achieve the economic prosperity that every New Yorker deserves!"
According to the New York Times, this was the largest action of its kind in the history of the U.S. fast food industry.
However, only a few hundred people were on the scene, far from all of whom are employed in the fast food industry, in which tens of thousands work in New York.
It is not yet clear whether the spark of these protests will mobilise whole masses.
"The brain has so far been only moderately outsmarted"
The popular topic of augmented reality among fans of modern technologies is usually perceived lately by the lens of a special glasses.
Google first presented a working model at its annual conference in the summer, then in November it was announced that Microsoft had also applied for a corresponding patent.
In conversation with the head of the group for interactive 3D technologies at the Microsoft laboratory in Cambridge Shahram Izadi, it becomes clear, however, that the glasses were only a transit station for the company’s scientists.
It attracts the possibility of manipulating virtual objects in the air with bare hands and creating virtual open spaces.
- Please describe briefly what research your group is doing.
- We are concerned with the interaction of man and machine, but want to expand the boundaries of this interaction.
So far, humanity has largely been stuck in the phase of working with pixels on flat screens, which are sometimes touched.
However, we want to look 5-10 years ahead and predict the radical changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are an advance, and no Xbox is sold without Kinect these days, as everyone is interested in motion control.
- What else can we expect in the future?
- Although Kinect has brought the interaction to a physical level, a lot is still happening on the flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information (the system receives more data) could be improved, the output has not yet been decisive.
We try to change that, working on real three-dimensional representation systems based on various technologies, including projections.
We need to release the computer world into our physical world and make it more tangible.
However, for this to happen, it is necessary that not only the user, but also his environment are recognized.
Then we could add virtual objects to the real world much more easily.
And first and foremost, we should get rid of these shitty virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
It’s popular, but isn’t it overrated?
- It is certainly not the all-purpose solution, as it raises questions about privacy, because you do not always want to inform everyone around you about his actions and intentions.
Actually, any kind of interaction with computers is good, but each in its particular niche.
For example, in the area of controlling objects in public places, we were working on a project where we experimented with short and short gestures instead of exhilarating gestures.
The gestures were not recorded by the object camera, but by a bracelet that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is still relatively large, but could theoretically be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But overall, the future belongs to mixed types of control, for example gesture and language.
- How's that?
- For example, we'd ask you to hand me this bubble?
They say it and point to it at the same time.
- Usually I just say it.
- Oh, that would be very hard to see.
- Does this mean that you want the user to adapt to what a machine can and cannot afford at a given time?
- Not necessarily, but it's a mutual approach.
I think that in the near future, we will have to work primarily on the development of new types of sensors that will enable us to capture people’s reactions more accurately.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, as they offer a good resolution in depth, which is very important.
- Based on your work with the Xbox Kinect sensors, what are your demands on modern cameras?
Is there a lack of resolution, depth, or something else?
- The current generation is basically a good starting point for our work in the field of three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, 8 megapixels at a speed of 1000 fps would not be bad.
But the main thing is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
From this point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us, as the developers of the algorithms have more work to do.
The resolution must be taken into account not only along the X- and the Y-, but also along the Z-axis.
The speed and the number of frames per second are also important.
Human movements are extremely dynamic and, frankly, the current 30 fps are not enough, especially for gestures.
Stephen Betishes developed a touch sensor at our Redmond lab with a controllable processing delay between 1 to 100 milliseconds, with today’s commercial sensors closer to the second value (60 to 100).
Not everyone understands how much this affects the interaction of man and machine.
For my work, I needed just such a device, only without touch control and with more images per second.
- Shouldn't the number of cameras be increased?
- Kinect currently works with three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second is a receiver for the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually an ordinary RGB camera.
It is not used to calculate object depth.
More cameras could possibly solve the problem...
Or amplify the problem, as more calculations would be needed.
Nice would be a flexible, Kinect-like system where we could play with different camera inclinations to see how that helps us determine a position in three-dimensional terms.
If I remember correctly, unlike Google, Microsoft did not present its glasses to the public.
Don’t you think that when it comes to applying the technology of augmented reality in everyday life, the glasses have the best prospects?
- Of course, it is not pleasant to always hold a smartphone in a raised hand on the go, but I think the best option would be a "changing" augmented reality, where we could switch from the glasses to the smartphone via a cloud,
The glasses are a personal gadget and in this lies their strength (privates only you can see), but at the same time their weakness, because an extended reality with glasses prevents you from working on virtual objects together with others.
- Let's imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holograms in the air is accessible not only to Tony Stark from Iron Man, but also to ordinary mortals.
There is one problem that critics often point out to this idea: there is no tangible reaction!
The hands feel nothing at all!
What answers does your group want to give to this objection?
- In my lectures, I often talk about the fact that augmented reality represents the seventh breakthrough in human-machine interaction.
I think the eighth breakthrough could well be the integration of tactile perception.
An interesting method is currently using the second hand as a somewhat unusual projection pad.
She perceives pressure excellently!
But there are also technologies that are actually designed to give the “images in the air” something handy, for example, the interference of some directed ultrasound beams at a certain point where the finger is, creates a feeling that is currently as weak as if someone was blowing over the palms of the hands.
There are also ligaments for the wrist that act on the nerve endings in the fingers, also this is a potential direction.
- Did you try to outsmart the brain?
Make it think it feels what it should feel when it sees something?
- That's a good idea, so we haven't tried it yet.
Here is another task that we will have to struggle with for a long time, namely making a person who is physically in an enclosed space believe that he is instead in an open, virtually infinite space; here we are working on concepts with treadmills (other than in gyms), moving platforms, and large balls.
So far, the brain can only be moderately outwitted, and we still have many busy years ahead of us.
This is precisely what makes the work in the field of virtual reality so attractive for a researcher: on many topics, we are only at the beginning.
