Birth in space
Earth in danger.
Global warming or collision with killer asteroid.
Caravans of spaceships with Earth dwellers on board set out in search of a replacement planet.
In order to save humanity, the important question arises how we can reproduce in weightlessness or on the substitute planet?
There are not many choices in my opinion.
In fact, there are only two real planets that we could at least hypothetically inhabit.
"Mars and Venus," says the research associate of the Astronomical Sternberg Institute, Vladimir Surdin.
However, while conditions on Mars are comparatively friendly, the surface of Venus has a temperature of 500 degrees.
Life would only be possible at high altitude or in the orbit of Venus, i.e. in space.
The researchers first addressed the issue of reproduction in space with regard to the flora.
Already half a century ago, experiments with plants were carried out.
The fourth generation of peas bred in orbit did not differ in the slightest from the earthly species.
It was followed by the breeding of insects, more precisely of tiny fruit flies (Drosophila), in orbit.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent to space to explore how weightlessness affects the development of embryos.
A normal chick develops.
But then the problem begins.
“The problem is that the chick needs to find hold; it needs to be able to stand on its legs and start moving,” explains Laboratory Director of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems RAN, Vladimir Sychev.
Without a solid surface, the chicks overwhelmed wildly.
Ten hours later, the instincts of the newborns completely dulled.
The chicks did not respond to light and noise.
Four days later, they simply died.
"Twice we let chicks hatch and then stopped it because it is simply impossible to work with them there," notes Vladimir Sychev about the failed experiment with the chicks in space.
The last breeding cage with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in the spring of 2013.
However, on the biosatellite "Bion" there will be only same-sex species.
There was an experiment with rats that were already fertilized into space.
In principle, nothing special was noted.
"This was just with the biosatellites, but again it was just a single experiment, and the research needs to be continued," remarks Vladimir Sychev.
After the landing, the space rats had offspring.
So far, the problem of reproduction directly in space has not been solved.
The task is difficult.
Animals that are ripped out of their natural habitat simply cannot follow their reproductive drive.
Unlike animals, humans can do this in principle.
The Homo sapiens is capable of abstract thinking and can create a similar emotional background.
For ethical reasons, such experiments are not carried out.
Women have been flying into space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was with Tereshkova.
The most valuable thing that humanity possesses is the female organism.
Our seagull flew away, and no one on Earth could have answered the following question: Does it survive the space flight?
Will she be able to give birth to a child after this flight?
"Finally, no one answered this question," said space veteran Wachtang Watschnadse.
In June 1964, just a year after her space flight, the first female cosmonaut, Valentina Tereshkova, gave birth to a daughter.
The father of the child, Andrijan Nikolaev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second woman in space, Svetlana Savizkaya, who was twice in orbit and even did work outside the spacecraft, gave birth to a son.
Nevertheless, there is still a risk.
We have only a very few cosmonauts, who after long flights all went well and got healthy offspring.
"The more, the more dangerous it is, even when flying into orbit," concludes cosmonaut Valeriy Polyakov, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of the Russian Federation.
And yet, humanity must look for new pathways in biotechnology, radiation protection and the generation of artificial gravity.
The hydro lab in the cosmonaut preparation center is a mandatory station during flight preparation.
Here, in a floating state, the cosmonauts are gaining routine for work in open space.
Water represents weightlessness.
Even though adults find water pleasant, it is an alien environment; yet infants perceive water as a natural element.
It is as if the little Ichtyanders testify that life on land emerged from the ocean.
There is a connection between the fact that a child is in the amniotic fluid in the mother's abdomen for about 9 months, and the fact that it can then more easily get used to water.
In principle, this is logical, since from birth to the first swim only 2 weeks pass.
"That's too little time to forget anything," says baby swimming teacher Marina Aksenowa.
While for a newborn child, weightlessness is a much more natural condition, the woman does not live without gravity.
In the state of weightlessness, the abdominal and pelvic muscles recur enormously quickly and thus the ability to push the child out also decreases.
All right, let's bypass that by birth-inducing aids.
For example, the birth could also take place in a special chamber to squeeze the child out.
"But what will happen then?" is the not insignificant question of Valeri Polyakov.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
Without feeling the earth’s attraction, the organism cannot train the skeleton and muscles.
A newborn child cannot be put into a suit in orbit like an adult for training.
He will simply miss what is of elemental importance to his life.
“This experiment, which we are jointly undertaking, namely the birth of a child in a foreign environment, will lead us to give birth to a disabled, a completely inappropriate human being,” predicts the head of the Bioethics Commission of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems, Igor Pestow.
So far, the birth of children in space is mere theory.
Eventually, however, it becomes a reality when the Earth-dwellers in their spaceships depart for a distant planet that will be the home of their offspring born in space.
