As far as Czech legislation is concerned, what was the significance for your authority of the amendment of the Public Procurement Act, do you already feel any impact?
Given that this novella is only in force for a short time, it has not yet had any effect on our tests.
Since our checks take place afterwards, you have to expect a certain delay here.
So far, we are more likely to experience an impact in the preparatory phase of future controls - for example, we have introduced the new control instrument "Identification of risks of uneconomicity" and with it almost 14,000 public contracts are examined and analyzed - here the changes will of course have an impact, as the thresholds change, the conditions for certain types of tenders have been modified, among other things.
Do you see the adoption of this law as rather positive, or is the system burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think this law is definitely a step in the right direction and I hope that this assumption is confirmed.
However, the problem may arise that the rules become "stricter" and can no longer be adhered to.
Already under the previous rules, persons subject to an audit are liable to the institution (for example, in the case of an operational programme of regional policy, the Regional Council) to the extent that any non-compliance with the Procurement Act is equivalent to a violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense to make the law even stricter?
I do not think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse the system, and not punish those who have committed a form error that does not affect actual decision-making.
Such a system merely puts the bureaucracy under even greater pressure.
Where's the way out?
First, let us say which path is not effective.
The prime minister recently said that the ODS would not bother the entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called "black system" - what exactly does that mean?
Is the black system banned or allowed?
After all, a law must have its validity, and if something is prohibited by law, then the head of government cannot simply come, and the supervisory office, whose duty is to check compliance with the law, can hinder its activity.
He can say, “We change the law and allow the thing,” but he can’t say that we’re pretending to be nothing.
The Procurement Act contains relatively strict rules on the formal execution of certain operations - and this is also true for the protection of public competition.
On the other hand, it is also tragic if the bidder with the best offer is excluded due to form defects alone.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be properly applied - and that's what I think we lack.
