<0xC5><0xA0>imon Ornest: We want to gather positive energy at our concerts
What do you think about the end of the world taking place in less than a month?
This is one of those disaster messages that we humans so much like to jump to.
With our band The Tap Tap, we are more likely to make fun of it and say that we are the only band in the world that can gather enough positive energy to stop or prevent the end of the world.
In December, you will also realize a unique project with three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you introduce the project to our readers?
This is a nationwide benefit event that we have been planning for two years.
For this, we want to use the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar, whose end is forecast for December 21 at 11:10 a.m.
The day before, i.e. on 20 December, three concerts will take place simultaneously in Prague, Brno and Ostrava from 21:00.
The end of the concerts is supposed to be about the time when on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which is in a time zone around 12 hours ahead of us, the Mayan calendar ends.
From whom does this idea come?
Originally from me, then we designed the idea together with our graphic designer Honza Augusta.
Not only do we want to gather enough positive energy to prevent the end of the world, but we also want to think together with the public about the state in which we will once hand this world over to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also developed a unique collection of shoes, t-shirts, bags and keychains against the end of the world, whose purchases through www.e-tap.cz can also support us.
The band The Tap Tap, along with other artists, has also recorded the so-called hymn against the end of the world with the title "Weltuntergang fällt aus".
Already today the anthem is very popular on YouTube. Will it sound at the charity concerts as well?
Of course, and at the end of the day, assuming that everything works out and that the end of the world does not happen...
The anthem will be sung by all performers at the same time at all three concerts.
In addition, the hymns are broadcast together in a live broadcast from Czech television.
The lyrics of the hymn come from Tomá<0xC5><0xA1> Hanák, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video clip, also Xindl X sings with...
How did you come to working with both?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is related to the fact that we realize many charity events and concerts...
We strive to involve these people intensively in our projects.
It has been shown that most people are interested in working with us and enjoy it.
What is the purpose of the proceeds of concerts against the end of the world?
For the establishment of the barrier-free education centre Studeo, at which we have been working for six years together with the association Tap at the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>ka Institute.
Students of the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>ka Institute are regularly supervised by lecturers who help them with various leisure activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the means to visit the editors, we would like to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>ka Institute, a separate building is to be built, in which we will then move with this project.
At each concert, several groups and performers perform.
What criteria have you chosen?
We wanted to put together a program that would appeal to all generations, including children.
In Prague, for example, Chinaski, Support Lesbians, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Ji<0xC5><0x99>í Such<0xC3><0xBD> will perform.
You can find out more on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar “great events” also planned for the future?
In May we perform for the first time at the Prague Spring, and also for this concert we are preparing an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to perform at the Czech House in New York, and I personally - if we are already in the USA - would also like to combine this with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your plans abroad are not exactly small, so far you have already appeared in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
However, The Tap Tap is a group composed of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these trips logistically and organizationally?
It’s not as bad as it seems at first glance.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, i.e. the wheelchairs must be transported in the luggage compartment. In addition, of course, we have to carry many instrument cases and other luggage...
Nevertheless, it has always worked out without any problems so far, <0xC4><0x8C>SA and British Airways were always very well prepared for us, that I have sometimes wondered already.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Through your trips abroad, you have a comparison of what it looks like in the individual countries with accessibility, how to deal with disabled people there, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than us, we witnessed in Russia that everything in the East is still in its beginnings.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is absolutely non-disabled, where it is still unusual for someone in a wheelchair to travel alone in the city centre.
It is not even self-evident that you leave a wheelchair user in the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, there are also associations that try to point out the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what way do we need to catch up with the more developed countries?
There are still a lot of things that we hang out in after...
However, it should also be noted that an improvement in the situation also depends on the efforts of those affected.
In London and Madrid, it is quite common for people with severe disabilities to move independently in public spaces, go to the museum, use the toilets, etc.
However, it is not very common that a larger group of disabled people actively participate in social events there, in which we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect in public and accessibility is one thing, but only when significant athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come from our ranks will things really start to change.
So far, these are only individual cases of particularly strong-willed personalities.
The Tap Tap is very popular right now, but if we go back a few years: what motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time I started as a supervisor at the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>ka Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in doing something intensive.
And since I am a musician myself and play the saxophone, among other things, I founded a music company together with a colleague.
Well, and over time, as our moderator, Lá<0xC4><0x8F>a Angelovi<0xC4><0x8D>, usually says, it gets a little out of control (laughs).
But the band has only become known in recent years, or am I mistaken?
It’s true that working with well-known singers has helped us, and we’ve also started to actively promote ourselves.
We have come to realize that if you do something and you cannot see it externally, your own performance does not exist in a certain sense.
Thanks to the EU funding, we can also afford good editors, high-quality equipment and the like.
Was it your goal to get it so far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I felt the potential that things could be done differently.
In the show business today, one often copies the other.
This is logical in its own way, since everything new is considered with caution and is only accepted after a long time.
There are few truly unique things, and I dare to say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression that the spectator usually gets is, of course, pity; this is only natural...
But this compassion is absolutely superfluous, because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings that we should regret.
They are people who can live and develop a full-fledged life, provided they have the necessary means to do so.
I always say that when people with disabilities succeed, it is not only progress for them, but for society as a whole.
Was it also helpful for this success that you are a strict boss, as you hear from many people?
If you want to do something good, you must not compromise on many things and also have to demand a certain discipline.
However, I think this is perfectly normal.
Some come to us with romantic ideas, and when they find that they have rehearsals twice a week, have to complete preparation phases and spend a lot of time on concert tours, then the enthusiasm for many quickly goes out.
But that’s how it works everywhere, in every band that wants to work seriously and achieve something.
The Tap Tap currently has 20 members.
