Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of the European Space Agency (ESA) at a Council of Ministers meeting, making it the second member of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland began working closely with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Poland’s journey into space, of course, began much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish cosmos enthusiasts were already involved in space travel, although they did not always come across understanding.
I recall here, for example, the lecture by A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld on 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, in which the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold, and after years <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
In 1934, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch, donated by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
In Polish journals he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski’s world-renowned contribution to the development of space travel was recognized, among other things, by naming one of the craters on the face of the moon after him.
Already in 1925, a railway drone was built in Poland, for which a rocket propulsion was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used for launching or braking the draisine.
The information on this comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-powered missiles.
The research was conducted by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
From the documents handed down, it can be seen that the research had progressed to the stage of practical tests.
The research was then, of course, interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, the design of a photoelectric hunting rocket by Ing. Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski appeared in the specialist press, and the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects were concerned with the military use of the rocket drive.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of missile technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Committee Doradczo-Naukowy).
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity, its work was terminated from the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space travel were published after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this society was made in 1954 in the November issue of the journal Problemy, in which four extensive articles are devoted to space travel.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal for the creation of a space society.
At the time, there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was to be foreseen that the exploration of space would have a future.
Already in its beginnings in 1956, the Polish Space Agency (PTA) sought to join the International Federation of Space, founded in 1951, and in fact the PTA became a regular member as early as the autumn of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Deputy Chairman of the International Federation for Space.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the most successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and weighed not quite 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959, flight tests began in the B<0xC5><0x82><0xC4><0x99>dów Desert with the two-stage RM-2 missile.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach a flight altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used for the observation of high winds.
In 1962, however, further development was discontinued.
The successor of the first RM rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the take-off weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed from this rocket, which differed in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport space with a capacity of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B had a capacity of 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C had a capacity of 0.62 liters.
The maximum flight altitude for all three types was 37 km.
From 1965 to 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aerospace Institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a take-off weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of approximately 60 km.
After that, the versions Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
Also worth mentioning is Poland’s accession to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, followed two years later by the establishment of a national COSPAR committee.
As part of the Interkosmos program, Poland also participated in space exploration with Soviet satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became second intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladimír Remek.
Repealing the law on non-profit work is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court lifted the law on non-profit work.
This decision provoked a lively discussion in the public.
It is certainly interesting to look at the problem from a broader perspective.
Liberal economic systems in the EU and in the globalised world are based on the principle of unregulated economic competition.
In the end, this means that the individual economies are in a permanent conflict with each other.
The reason for this is the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital, which goes hand in hand with unbridled financial speculation.
Due to the large differences in the value of work (wages), there are price tensions.
This term refers to a situation in which the producer seeks to maintain economic competition by importing favourable goods by "underscoring" the competition in order to gain a greater market share and increase its profits.
On a large scale, this means for most companies to relocate their manufacturing or buy cheaply abroad, or to abandon their business, resulting in high unemployment in countries with comparablely high labour costs.
Since private capital bears no social responsibility and therefore no responsibility for the unemployment it causes, government spending necessarily increases.
This situation is aggravated by the fact that the gentlemen entrepreneurs are absolutely reluctant to pay their taxes and thus compensate for the economic and social damages they cause to society as a whole.
This situation is generally known, so that concrete statistics are superfluous at this point.
The ruthless practice of private capital creates a situation in the individual economies in which governments are forced to compete with each other in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population and thus attract foreign capital into the country.
In other words, governments hand over their own population to private capital, regardless of the social consequences.
This is reflected in particular in amendments to existing laws.
The aim of these measures is to force one’s own population to accept the dictates of private capital, especially in the wage area.
This is done on the one hand by economic coercion in the case of long-term unemployment, on the other hand by the reduction of workers' rights.
The result is growing poverty and growing disparities between rich and poor.
In Germany, there have been public food delivery points for the poor for several years, which are no longer able to feed themselves through their own work.
The number of those affected is already going into the millions.
In the course of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, there are regular cases where employees receive such a low wage that the state has to increase their income to the minimum living.
Such a scandal has also been uncovered in the case of aid workers employed in the German Bundestag.
The austerity measures of virtually all EU southern states will undoubtedly result in the same situation where, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of their social level, people are forced to emigrate (as was the case in the 19th century), or to give up for a starvation wage on the fringes of society, hoping that at some point private investment capital will flow into the country.
This naturally raises the question of where this capital comes from.
If it comes from another EU country, only poverty migrates from one country to another; or capital stays out completely, because in China, India, Brazil, Turkey, Morocco or Egypt, or Africa at all, the workers work for a fraction of European wages.
This applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and media up to the point that the state is not allowed to participate in its own economy with capital, and that the planned economy leads to economic disaster.
Private capital insists narrowly on its position that the state must not intervene in the economy in a guiding way.
But then one has to wonder if private capital does not influence or even direct politics and thus the entire state in its own selfish sense.
Here is the clear answer: yes.
Proof of this is the existence of a virtually all-powerful and omnipresent lobby in all states.
The result is a desperate situation in the area of corruption, mutual favoritism, legislation in which virtually everything is punishable, but nothing is punishable.
In Germany, the situation is such that a State Ministry, due to a lack of finance, commissions private legal companies, closely intertwined with industry, to draft bills.
These bills are then passed in the Bundestag.
All violence then no longer emanates from the people, as the Western constitutions proclaim, but from strong financial groups that prefer their own interests.
Apparently, the liberal democracies are rapidly falling into a situation as described by Appian in his work on the Crisis of the Roman Republic at the time of Caesar and Pompey: "The state has long been in disintegration, and the offices have been occupied by force.
In exchange for bribes, by unlawful use of advantages or with stone and sword.
The corruption grew uncontrollably, and the people went to the polls with already bought votes" ... "All people with character did not apply for offices, so that the state had no consul for eight months as a result of this decline" ... "It was actually started to talk that the only medicine in this difficult situation was a solitary domination, and that a strong man had to be chosen by Pompey, but the man in the Appian thought"...
As it turns out, today’s society, just as in antiquity, is based on the ruthless preference of one’s own advantage, without paying attention to the interests of society as a whole.
Private capital, by its very nature, is incapable of recognizing and enforcing the advantage for society as a whole.
The result, both today and then, is an unprecedented decadence of the elites, who are not in the least striving for deeper reforms.
The cause of the rise of fascism and communism must therefore be sought in the ruthless liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
From the current state of affairs, the demise of these regimes in favour of liberal democracies can be seen as a certain pause in which the next round is already emerging.
Particularly disastrous is the fact that today’s elites are in complete ignorance of the possible loss of hundreds of thousands of lives in the future, the humanitarian and social disasters of which we are already witnesses today, as well as the crimes against humanity as we know them from the older and more recent history.
The repeal of the law on non-profit work is not a solution here, at least not a permanent one.
Under pressure from global and European economic competition, the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to seek ways to push the social level of the population down.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The only solution is targeted political-social reforms that increase the state’s capital participation in the economy, increase citizens’ influence on the government, and weaken the monopoly of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
