The movie Argo: When it's worst to call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of demonstrating Islamist students occupied the U.S. embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the overthrown Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, who had been patron of his regime for decades.
For the American government, there was no positive way out of this situation – it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have massively damaged the trust of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, she was unable to enforce the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a severe blow to the reputation of the United States, and the subsequent failure in the violent attempt to free the hostage only made things worse.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days after negotiations had been mediated by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages sparked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments at home.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's defeat of Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the United States a small partial victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the embassy, six embassy staffers managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees out of Iran, assisting them with an extravagant story to cover up their true identity — they traveled with Canadian passports disguised as members of a film staff who allegedly visited the country’s filming locations for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by the expert on "exfiltration", Tony Mendez, also required Hollywood's cooperation.
So that the camouflage became credible, articles about this film project appeared in trade journals, press conferences were held, and the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have been kept secret for a long time. The film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful hussard piece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
As a result, the mood levels in the film vary - on the one hand, the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence, iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and even in the film version of the same situations, there are no big differences).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which come ironically and slightly pointedly.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, in the corridors, on the phone...
With this film, Ben Affleck has succeeded in a remarkable reboot of his career.
A laughed-out actor has become a respectable director, and even as an actor, he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the crime novel No Child’s Play (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the thriller City Without Mercy (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck’s first film not to be set in the director’s native Boston.
The feel for the atmosphere of the place was one of the features that set this director’s previous films apart from Hollywood’s standard.
However, Affleck also proves this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that really took place - the input sequence of the storming of the message is very impressive in their clarity, yet still conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when somewhere the story moves.
Affleck and his team also achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (the wrong film staff on a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not actually offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
But with the few, he works quite successfully, sometimes imitating reality - which then does not always seem so elegant (the scenes where the impending crisis at Tehran airport is averted by a phone call in America, or even the chase on the runway, seem a bit artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its too wide scattering, which is caused by the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters deserve more space, and they are by no means alone in the film.
Affleck’s film is losing some traction, a film that can be followed with a certain interest and gouty the design and the retro style, reminiscent of a thriller from the 70s.
However, it is difficult to arouse enthusiasm.
However, it is sufficient as a reminder of a piece of history that is still alive to this day in a certain way, and as proof of how exaggerated are the notions of the all-powerful and all-knowing intelligence services.
