The MVRDV architects prove that the true adventures are not only in the mind - using the example of Spijkenisse and the recently built Buchberg - 2 photos
"I find the building funny, it looks futuristic, and finally there's something interesting to see again," says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the roadside.
And Stefan Spermon, IT technician in a nearby large company, says: "Yes, it's nice, the house."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
All have internet, iPad and e-books.
No one goes to any of these old-style libraries today, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleep town that hardly needs to be visited at the gates of Rotterdam, is a strange record holder.
The 80,000-inhabitant community has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to counter this stupidity, a few years ago, it was decided to contribute to general education and to recreate the seven fictitious bridges depicted on the euro banknotes as beautifully brushed reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the education campaign was limited.
And so the city fathers realized that there was only one way to become masters of statistics: a library had to be made!
Winy Maas from the Rotterdam architectural firm MVRDV, master of bold bar charts and producer of funny, even often cynical buildings, took the matter with the usual serenity and appeared at the competition hearing in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And while the jury was still staring around and shrugging his shoulders, the insolent Maas piled up his exquisite gifts of the size of a pyramid and ended his actionist-backed speech with the words: "Dear city community!"
So that's him, my proposal for the Buchberg of Spijkenisse, for the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30-million-euro mountain is scattered.
It is part of a revitalization project, which also includes underground parking, supermarket, post office and a few adjacent residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the Buchberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, the faceless small town retort, which hitherto had nothing more to offer than a post-modern pedestrian zone and an astonishingly ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one would be inclined to suspect a dairy factory to make a piece of contemporary architecture richer.
Above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
The Long Way to the Book
The first impression: book eldorado under cheese bell.
Although there is a lift that runs through the middle of the mountain massif, the true pleasures of space and reading open up as you walk up the topography.
The all-glassed interior is bright and clear, the burnt clinker floor and the elegant street lamps speak unmistakably the language of a public city square.
The urban ambience is perfect.
You are already looking for park bench, dog and soccer playing boys and girls.
And everywhere books, books, books.
"Normally, the bookshelves stand along the facade, and in the middle is a large, dark room that is usually uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
We turned the classic room configuration upside down and pushed the reading area from the inside out.
The interior of the Buchberg is cleverly used: in the middle are offices, internet library, chess club, environmental center and house technology center.
A special delight are the black bookshelves, which are sometimes wall cladding, sometimes bristles, sometimes ladder railings.
Optics, haptics and smells are foreign.
Even hardworking architects and civil engineers shake their heads over the unknown building material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials here," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, at the request of the standard.
And so we came across a suitable waste product from agriculture in a Frisian farm one day.
For many years, in the Netherlands, a millimeter-thin plastic fleece has been used as a root support in greenhouses and fields.
This is cheap and time efficient.
The thin textile lasts one or two seasons, after which it is ripe for blocking waste.
For the library, the fleece - for the first time in these quantities - was pressed to four centimeters thick plates.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, strain-resistant material that smells like new cars and sports shoes.
After 105 steps you have reached the summit.
At the end of the almost 500 meter long hike, you will be rewarded in the Literaturcafé not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and potted ficus trees.
They provide an atmosphere, but above all they provide the right humidity in the literary mountains.
Donations for the New Soul
"You wouldn't believe it, but despite the many glass surfaces, this house is a flagship project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
Heated and cooled with geothermal heat.
Although the Buchberg is under a glass turmoil, even on sunny days the sun shines only briefly inside.
The wide wood glue ties, which are transverse to the glass facade, serve as shade and intercept much of the sunlight.
The room climate is very pleasant.
The rest is done by fully automatic roller shutters.
Stefan Spermon, the initial skeptic from the IT industry, already dared to enter the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was there too.
And also the TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even describes the Boekenberg as the "longest overdue soul".
The reason: For the opening a few weeks ago, each resident was invited to donate a book from his personal inventory.
For the time being, the optical gaps in the library – currently 70,000 pieces – are to be filled.
The concept has emerged.
The shelves are filled up to the top.
“Nothing is worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Winy Maas.
"I think, thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship with this new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
And if it's just for decoration.
In this way, MVRDV has succeeded in the royal discipline, which is called in the specialist jargon identity foundation.
Spijkenisse has written literary history.
As young and unskilled as she may be.
This is finally a starting point for identity.
Szabo: "Germans have to play a bigger role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the inclusion of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, expert on U.S.-European relations, Berlin is balancing this on a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany had first signalled that it would vote against the request for Palestinian observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why? Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, Germany has to be cautious because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don’t think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the Libyan uprising in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to setting up a no-fly zone.
This was eventually enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is shifting its foreign policy from a policy managed by the US, so to speak, to a German foreign policy.
To make matters worse, Europeans do not have a coherent and unified policy.
Thus, the Germans find themselves between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they were still tackling their role, but they are on the way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy like that of France or Britain.
What does a “normal” foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It shows a willingness to take up positions in national interests that are independent of those of the United States or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany’s economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of the other great powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the attitude in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
On the one hand, Germany has large sales markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf states.
Therefore, it must be careful not to hit the heads of the public, but also the elites, in the Arab countries.
That definitely matters.
But I wouldn’t want to put too much weight on that either, it’s not a completely one-sided relationship.
But it definitely plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the United States by abstaining in important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that there is a great understanding of the German position in Europe and even in the United States.
That is why I do not believe that this was such a dramatic break as in the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will even show some respect for it.
Because it signals that it is taken seriously as an international player and its interests must be taken into account.
There are different opinions in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
The U.S., on the other hand, has clearly voted in favour of a veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the United States and many European nations?
Due to American domestic policy, these differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama administration secretly has quite a bit of understanding for the European position.
But, of course, because of the political situation here, the government cannot publicly represent this position.
