Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and gonorrhea.
Common viral STIs are HIV, human papillomavirus, genital herpes, or hepatitis.
Felt lice and scabies belong to the parasitic STI.
Who are the main affected groups?
Syphilis and trippers occur mainly in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute estimates that at least four out of five cases of syphilis reported in Germany are transmitted through sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia infections, trichomonads, candidiasis (fungus), trippers, and human pappiloma viruses are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The prevalence of HIV among heterosexual adults in this country is comparatively low - yet: Around 20 percent of new HIV infections are caused by this group.
Chlamydia infections occur significantly more frequently among adolescents than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three-quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
In addition, human pappiloma viruses are common in adolescents in this country.
How has the number of infections evolved?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to notification.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections has more than doubled from 1,697 diseases in 2001 to 3,698 diseases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has declined since 2007.
In 2011, there were around 2700 cases.
That’s about a tenth less than the year before.
What are the symptoms of a sexually transmitted disease?
Infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, urination discomfort, discharge, lower abdominal pain, as well as blisters or warts.
Often, however, they do not cause pain or other symptoms and therefore go unnoticed.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but do not offer 100% protection.
Because in part, pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be passed on through lubricating infections and close body contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular examinations, especially with frequently changing sex partners.
Early diagnosis can cure most STIs and avoid late consequences.
