But what is an insult and how it should be punished remains unclear.
Similarly, the phrase “insulting people” seems to be prohibited.
Is a caricature of the president enough or a joke at the expense of a lawyer?
The matter of interpretation, as so much in the draft, which Mursi is present for signature and will, according to his words, be presented "very soon" to the Egyptians for a referendum.
"The revolution has returned"
The opposition has been forming for weeks against the supremacy of the Islamists.
Tens of thousands gathered in unusual harmony on Friday evening in Cairo’s Tahrir Square, vowing to bring down the Charter before it can enter into force.
"The revolution has returned and we will win," said Hamdin Sabbahi, third-placed presidential candidate.
Nobel Peace Prize winner and former head of the International Atomic Energy Agency, Mohamed El-Baradei, said the draft constitution belonged “to the garbage mountain of history.”
Via Twitter, he accused Mursi's supporters of wanting to lead a "coup against democracy".
"If he calls the referendum, we will go to his palace and overthrow him," opposition leader Jasser Said said.
"We are not tired yet, the blood of our brothers has not yet been atoned for," the Egyptian media quoted opposition politician Chaled Ali as saying.
And several judges announced that they would not want to oversee the referendum, which would invalidate it.
"The Qur'an is our Constitution"
The well-organized Muslim Brotherhood, for its part, blew to counter-demonstration, but not on Tahrir Square, but after a mass prayer on the other side of the Nile in front of the Cairo University.
Many veiled women and Salafists attended, shouting, “The people are demanding the application of God’s law.”
They demanded from Mursi: “Cleanse the land!” and asserted: “The Qur’an is our constitution.”
A struggle for sovereignty over the emblematic Tahrir Square, where everything began, would probably have sparked civil war-like conditions.
Obviously, Mursi’s supporters did not want to risk that.
The Muslim Brotherhood stated that both the opponents of the draft constitution and the supporters had spoken out loud and clear.
Now is the time to let the people at the ballot box decide which direction the country should go.
A majority in favour of the Islamist draft is considered safe.
"The word human rights does not even exist"
Hafez Abu Saeda is furious about this forced constitutional process, which should have been going through February and involving all social forces.
The 48-year-old human rights lawyer and chairman of the Egyptian Organization for Human Rights (EOHR) defended the Muslim Brotherhood when they were in prison or on trial under Mubarak.
Not because he would share their worldview, but because human rights are indivisible for him.
For this he was beaten, convicted, imprisoned.
"And now the word human rights is not even in the new constitution," he laments in a conversation with the "Welt am Sonntag".
Mursi's extension of power to all three powers in the state caused the lawyer to resign.
These measures are flagrant violations of democratic rules of the game and will lead Egypt into a new dictatorship.
"Instead of strengthening civil society, the president is de facto dismantling it," Saeda lamented.
But without civil society organizations, a democracy cannot work.
Saeda feels left alone, also by the international community, which looks at the ideological directional struggle on the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
That could take revenge.
A protester on the Tahrir warns, "You are bearing a monster that you can no longer control."
Rakfisk from Norway: Is this the most smelly fish in the world?
The five million inhabitants of Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living – not only in Europe, but all over the world.
Could the country’s secret to success have anything to do with the local appetite for rather nasty fish?
Take a selection of overripe cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a pile of dirty, damp sportswear.
And leave her there for a week.
About that, you have to imagine the nose-deafening smell of Rakfisk, one of Norway’s great delicacies.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
There is snow here, spectacular landscapes - and that stubborn smell in the air that just doesn't want to disappear.
Rakfisk is a trout sprinkled with salt, which - depending on how smelly you like your fish - is fermented in water for up to a year.
When the darkness comes over the country in Norway and the weather gets colder, Norwegians flock to a festival here in Fagernes, dedicated to this, well, really very captivating specialty.
"You eat it raw and then rinse it down with a glass of aquavit," says Havard Halvarsen, who actually works in the local fire department, but also hosts the festival as a so-called "Rakfisk-General".
People around us eat small fish cubes and consume large amounts of alcohol.
"Many people like the Aquavit more than the Rakfisk," says Havard.
The spirits can suppress the smell.
I'll have some snacks.
If you avoid bringing the Rakfisk close to your nose, it's not bad - like sushi, which has a pretty long bus ride behind it.
Rakfisk is the product of a completely different, much poorer Norwegian era, when there were no cooling facilities and fish was soaked in airtight salt water barrels in autumn.
In the deepest winter, it was then removed after long fermentation and - undoubtedly with the help of alcohol subdued senses - consumed.
Just a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians in search of work were forced to leave their country and emigrated mainly to the United States.
Today, the population is growing rapidly – more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by a thriving labour market, high wages and comprehensive healthcare.
Even from Sweden, the old rival, who was far richer than Norway not too long ago, immigrants are flocking.
Rakfisk is regarded as something important – an essential, albeit highly smelling, part of Norwegian history.
It is one of the most expensive dishes you can buy here.
But actually, everything here is expensive - a small glass of beer or a sandwich costs proudly 10 euros.
Norway doesn’t make it to the world press often, and most people don’t seem to bother with that.
Anders Breivik, the racist right-wing extremist who shot 77 men, women and children last year, is still hated here.
Instead, we only refer to the "incident of July 22".
Norwegians find it difficult to accept that someone in their peace-loving country is capable of such brutal murders.
The main reason for Norway’s wealth has been the growth of one of the largest oil and gas industries in the world since the early 1970s.
"But oil isn't the only reason we're doing so well," says Anna, our waitress, who distributes round trays of ripe rakfisk and embodies the Nordic ideal with her long blonde hair and stinging blue eyes.
We are, as they say, a wise people.
Her English is just like that of most people here.
We're not very pretentious, we don't like bragging.
Norway has handled its oil wealth very carefully – a large part of the industry’s revenue is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When, in the years leading up to the Great Depression, everyone was thrown around with money they didn’t even have, Norway kept its wallet tightly closed.
"As long as we can ski in winter and go hiking in summer, we are happy," says Anna.
"And, of course, eat rakfisk," she adds with carefree laughter.
I stand in the snow and stand for another dish - I've had enough of Rakfisk.
Such a moose burger is definitely something different. The juicy meat mouths me.
But in the evening the stinky fish is on the menu again.
The hotel where I stay is one of several venues that organize a Rakfisk dinner where guests can vote for the best – or perhaps the most challenging – fish.
There is a live TV circuit to a fly-clad showmaster surrounded by plates of Rakfisk.
It is similar to the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What score do you have up there in the mountains for the best fish, Thor-Jürgen?"
"Here are our points, Havard".
You clap and laugh.
A man falls from his chair, possibly overwhelmed by the aquavit.
But maybe it's the harsh fog of the whole fish.
Mexico's Enrique Pena Nieto faces tough start
As Mexico’s future president, Enrique Pena Nieto, prepares to take office, Will Grant of the BBC analyzes the challenges ahead and the mixed feelings of his people.
Currently, traffic in Mexico City is particularly bad.
Even on better days, this is an ever-clogged city, but on Monday, a steel ring was erected that shuts off several important traffic routes to the capital and creates chaos on the roads.
The goal, however, was not to disrupt commuters on their way to work, but to prevent protesters from reaching Parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico’s new president, Enrique Pena Nieto, will receive the presidential tie and take over the nation’s leadership.
He faces a complex task.
Under the outgoing government of Felipe Calderon, Mexico has proven itself economically well, but the country is in the grip of a drug war that has already cost 60,000 lives in the last six years.
"My government is strongly committed to reducing violence," Peña Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama in the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy to help us achieve this goal.
Before joining the U.S. president, Peña Nieto served as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In this densely populated, vast part of the country that surrounds the capital, opinions about the new head of state are divided.
A direct man
In the remote small town of Valle del Bravo, for example, one likes to remember him.
Residents of the resort attribute it to the development of tourism and the construction of infrastructure.
To reach the city, one can drive on one of the highways that Pena Nieto had built and which represents a great improvement over the brittle, bumpy roads that once existed here.
Plaques bearing his name also hang outside a modern sports center and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We expect real and sustained changes from him," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, who works as a congressman for the Peña Nieto's party, the PRI.
In particular, as regards security and the economy, we hope for an interesting and real change that our country so desperately needs.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was replaced by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, the party has high expectations of Enrique Pena Nieto.
He rejects the opposition’s accusations that the new president is lacking in substance.
He is a very direct man, very committed and has big plans for the country.
He is an excellent statesman, but above all, he is also someone who can listen.
But on the other side of the state, not many people share this view of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast to the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
The place is hidden under highway crossings and in many ways represents a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the community are of decisive urban nature.
Earlier this year, the military was engaged to fight the drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is a particularly acute problem.
The bodies of dozens of murdered women have been left alone in a patch of wasteland near a large landfill in the past two years.
During the reign of Governor Pena Nieto, over 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico - a statistic that even surpasses that of the city of Ciudad Juarez, which is notorious for its violence and the murders of innocent women.
Critics of Pena Nietos believe that he has at least not addressed the problem of female murders during his term in office.
In the worst case, however, his government closed its eyes to the problem.
In a concrete building, typical of the declining neighborhood, Irinea Buendia struggles with the tears when she shows me photos of her deceased daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the events, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
But her family believes she was murdered by her partner.
"When I arrived at her home, it seemed as if her body had been washed," Buendia recalls.
There were signs that she was beaten, and the body rigidity had already started.
As her mother tells her story, a picture of Mariana looks down on us from the wall, next to a cross bearing a single word: justice.
But this, the family, has been denied to her until now.
The authorities have treated me as if I were a chatterer, a troublemaker, a nörgler.
They want you to just accept their judgment and keep your mouth shut.
“But that’s not possible if there were so many form errors and omissions,” she says.
When President Peña Nieto receives the Presidential bind on Saturday, he also assumes a great responsibility.
Tens of thousands of Mexican families have been victims of violent crimes over the past six years, and the new president has promised to take special care of this problem during his term.
"I hope as president he is as he was as governor," said the PRI Congressman Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
But that is what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza fear most.
Prosecutor claims Bradley Manning did not complain about abuse
Prosecutor Dismisses Bradley Manning’s Accusations of Being Abused in Prison
The hearing deals with Manning's time at the Military Prison in Quantico, Virginia
The defense seeks a rejection of the indictment due to too harsh detention conditions
U.S. Army soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents
The prosecutor's office tried on Friday to establish that Army pistolman Bradley Manning - accused of the largest disclosure of confidential information in U.S. history - missed several occasions to complain about the abuse he allegedly suffered in military detention.
During a cross-examination of Manning during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Maj. Ashden Fein explained that records of weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning's nine-month imprisonment in Quantico, Virginia, showed no complaints about his treatment.
A day before the cross-examination, which was held as a result of a request from the defense to reject the indictment - Manning had already been adequately punished by the harsh imprisonment - Manning had testified that he had considered suicide in prison.
The U.S. Army intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his time in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as the source of the information.
In the Friday hearing, Fein and Manning reviewed the forms that officials had filled out after their meetings with Manning during his detention at the Quantico Military Prison, where he had been incarcerated from July 2010 to April 2011 under increased detention conditions.
The officers asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein asked him about the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had judged the treatment by his guards as "excellent" and the treatment by the establishment as a whole as "very professional".
The forms, Fein said, contained no complaints about mistreatment, although officials had directly questioned Manning about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally and that the officials had discussed them with him and indicated that they would deal with them, but they had not been recorded.
“They wrote (after discussing the concerns) ‘No problems’, and that didn’t necessarily mean I didn’t say anything at all,” Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to investigate the suicidal thoughts he mentioned on a form a few months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during this meeting was to downgrade his observation status to “prevent injury.”
The military said it had assigned him this restrictive status – which is one stage below suicide risk – to his and the protection of others.
“I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well and get rid of observational status for the prevention of injuries (...) in order to achieve a higher quality of life in my view,” Manning said.
Manning said on Thursday he was arrested and transferred to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the prison of the Quantico naval base in Virginia in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and had once become unconscious due to the heat.
Not being able to know what was happening to him or the outside world has been burdensome.
"My world shrunk at Camp Arafjon, on this cage together," Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
When he was transferred to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell — at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours — and without company.
They only allowed him a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said he was trying to keep moving because by day it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down.
He always had to sleep with light that entered his cell from the outside.
When he turned around at night and the guards could no longer see his face, they woke him up so he would turn back.
In January 2011, Manning's lawyer formally appealed against Manning's treatment.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to the Fort Leavenworth Military Prison in Kansas.
On Friday, Judge Manning also questioned an allegation he had made in his testimony on Thursday - so he had to sleep naked one night in his cell in Quantico and stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners at a morning count.
Manning had testified that he had never had the opportunity to cover himself with his blanket during this count.
During the interview on Friday, Manning said he had concluded from an order from his guard that he should drop the blanket with which he could have covered himself, but he admitted that no one had asked him to do so.
On Thursday, Manning had testified that he was forced to sleep naked the previous night and had previously tried to show an official that he posed no danger to himself.
Manning had told the official that he could have used the waistband of his underpants or flip-flops to hurt himself, but he did not.
That night, Manning said, his underpants, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account his detention experiences and drastically reduce his level of detention if he is convicted in his trial before the military court, which is scheduled for early next year.
The defense has indicated that Manning will plead guilty to minor offences, while other charges deemed too extreme are to be challenged.
The continuation of the hearing is scheduled for this weekend, and the prosecution is expected to justify the conditions of detention.
The Pentagon remains in its position that Manning has been detained in accordance with the provisions that apply to all prisoners detained under the highest security guards in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include fomenting the enemy, unlawful publication of intelligence information on the Internet, transmission of national defense information, and theft of public property or documents.
If he is found guilty in all charges, he faces life imprisonment.
My Mexican-American identity crisis.
Many people are forced to leave Mexico because of the lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to blame the immigrants – they remind them of hard times, he says
Navarrette believes Mexican Americans are trapped between two worlds
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had just crossed the hall and had arrived at the passport control when confusion spread within me.
Signs pointed to two queues: one for "Mexicanos" ("Mexicans"), another for "Extranjeros" ("Foreigners").
I stood there for a few seconds, unsure where to go.
I grew up in Central California and have been called “Mexicains” all my life.
An ethnic abbreviation - just like my friends in Boston call themselves "Irene" or my friends in New York call themselves "Italians".
Later, I decided to go for "Mexican-American."
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather’s home there was no need for shortcuts or hyphens.
I was just American.
I speak Spanish, at least good enough to maintain myself in this language at both ends of an interview.
But I don’t have the vocabulary of a native speaker, and I won’t get rid of my American accent either.
So I took my American passport and put myself in line for Extranjeros.
I was thinking about that moment this week when future Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
On the agenda were all those issues that were expected when the heads of these two countries met: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto was also very interested in talking about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one reason why Mexicans are equally likely to stay in Mexico today instead of emigrating to the United States.
He wants to unite with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc modelled on the European Union.
And Pena Nieto vowed to continue the war of Mexico against the drug cartels, even if he did not mention any details on this.
Mexico’s relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never waste a single thought on the fact that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848, forcing the country’s leadership to leave more than half of its territory to them.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries and not in minutes, memories of this event are not to be overlooked.
So, as soon as a U.S. government official makes the slightest criticism of Mexico, one hears complaints – in the Mexican press and among the country’s elites – about how Americans are harassing the sovereignty of their neighboring country.
And Montezuma's children are on the war path.
And yet, Mexico’s biggest challenge in reality lies in its relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Want to talk about resentment?
There's more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers, people for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason so many people of Mexican origin live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that at one point in our family tree, a person—perhaps a parent or grandparent—was given no chance in Mexico and emigrated north.
And in most cases, this person corresponded to a profile - dark-skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our loyalty applies to them.
Not Mexico.
And while we may now be living the American Dream, attending good schools and getting good jobs, we must never lose sight of the fact that it is the American Dream we are living – not the Mexican Dream.
Our identity may sometimes be blurred, but as far as our loyalty is concerned, it is not.
This clearly applies to the United States.
Moreover, we are aware that many members of the Mexican leadership do not like us.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look down on us because we are not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their opinion, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families had not failed in Mexico, they would not have gone.
And then we wouldn’t see ourselves trapped behind the silk curtain – with a pleasant life in the United States, but somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there are tensions between Mexicans and Mexican Americans because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are – and Mexican Americans take this offense to them.
While she is a U.S. citizen, she sees herself as part of two countries.
But many Mexican Americans I know have the feeling that neither belong to one country nor to the other.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
One enjoys the best of both worlds, but is not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico, we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States, we are seen as Mexicans.
As I was supposed to learn during my journey, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: some Mexican leaders and parts of the educational bourgeoisie want to re-establish their connections to the diaspora.
They want to use Mexican Americans as provisional “ambassadors” for Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We should tell our American colleagues how great a visit to this country is and pressure the political leadership to intensify their ties to Mexico.
Oh, well.
That's not gonna happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And given the unfair distribution of income, unbridled corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure if this is really a great country.
I'm afraid you'll have to go through that alone, amigos.
That's fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not yet ready to forgive the United States for dealing with Mexico a century and a half ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans have a grudge at how their family members were treated not so long ago.
- Hmmm.
Maybe we're more Mexican than I thought.
Old Battles, New Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could prove to be an unexpected foundation for peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
The latest bloody events seem to suffocate such hope in the germination.
In the midst of the usual accusations, countless buildings have been demolished, more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis killed – and for the first time, rockets from Gaza have hit near the Israeli metropolis of Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But even though Israelis and Palestinians seem trapped in their historical conflict, the Middle East is changing around them.
The Arab Spring has created a new, uncertain situation, and whether they want it or not - Palestinians and Israelis have become part of this turmoil.
Perhaps this will only lead to more bloodshed.
But there are reasons to believe that the deadly stalemate could finally come to an end.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism seems anything but appropriate given the current situation.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on 21 November continues, this week’s fighting has strengthened the hard-boiled on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has been controlling the Gaza Strip since 2007, will claim to have pushed back the Israelis, despite the fact that its group itself suffered heavy losses.
Although several Hamas leaders are killed and the 1.7 million inhabitants of the Gaza Strip are grafted into one of the most desolate and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has not yet succeeded in destroying Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, which is controlled by the rival, moderate Palestinian group Fatah.
And the Hamas leaders could conclude that they have time on their side.
Just as Islamists have gained influence in the Arab world, Hamas has been able to draw powerful and rich friends to its side.
Turkey, a resurgent regional power once considered Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has taken sides for Hamas – just like Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Hailing Hamas supporters believe that an Islamist crescent is forming around Israel – from Lebanon in the north, where Hezbollah militants have power, to Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist rank could stand in front of the overthrow of Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And in particular, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Mursi in Egypt – by far the most populous and most important Arab country – on the southern flank of Israel has changed the balance of the region sustainably.
Hosni Mubarak, the lay despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time left for Hamas.
In contrast, the Brotherhood is conspiring with Hamas and its leaders are more dependent on popular views.
In future diplomatic negotiations, Hamas could prove to be an actor that cannot be pushed out even by Israel and the United States.
The Israeli hardliner, on the other hand, draws the opposite conclusion.
From a military point of view, Hamas is no longer a threat.
The Israeli missile defense system, “Iron Dome,” has proved itself and many of the Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
At least for a while, Israel will be able to sleep more quietly.
From a diplomatic point of view, the United States is firmly holding on to its position, and many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest escalations of violence.
Israel has been doing well in recent years, especially under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free of suicide bombings – not least thanks to the blockades that run into the West Bank and thus into the main part of a possible Palestinian state. These protect the Jewish settlements, which have been declared ever more illegal.
Netanyahu’s Likud party has allied itself with an even more militant group in the run-up to the January 22 elections under Avigdor Lieberman.
Why do these treacherous Palestinians cuddle and leave their own state to them?
If they were actually in control of the West Bank, wouldn’t they be firing rockets just like their counterparts in the Gaza Strip?
No, it is better to keep them at bay behind the wall and punish them if they dare to raise their heads.
Perhaps the hardliners will be able to prevail, but the Arab Spring could make a mark on them.
Even if the Islamists, who are now in power in Egypt and other countries, have little left for Israel, they will initially focus on the difficulties in their own country.
Israel’s defense budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
A war with the local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments in restoring their economy.
The fact that pragmatic President Morsi teamed up with Barack Obama to reach a ceasefire could be a promising sign – and perhaps symbolize the beginning of a new era.
Israelis should also think long-term.
While the rest of the Arab world is taking timid steps toward democratization, Palestinians continue to be deprived of their right to self-determination — a powder barrel that will undoubtedly one day explode in the Israeli-occupied territories, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
The oppression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and with the growth of the Arab population, this situation will only worsen.
Bloody missions to repel Hamas in the Gaza Strip will increasingly demand their diplomatic tribute over the years.
Both sides need a push from the outside
The correct answer is that of the more reasonable representatives of both sides, most of the rest of the world and this newspaper: two states where Israel cedes territories for security purposes.
The hope – small for the near future – is that the ceasefire will give outsiders more influence to enforce this solution.
Egypt, together with Turkey and Qatar, must now stop arms deliveries to the Gaza Strip and is better positioned than ever to convince Hamas of the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, complemented by territory exchange and a common Jerusalem.
Foreign Arab nations should also push Hamas and Fatah to reach an agreement.
This would do more for the creation of a Palestinian state than with the forthcoming application for UN observer status.
Obama, too, must play his part in pushing Israel into negotiations.
During his first term, he missed the idea of his own peace plan.
Far away in the White House, he seems to be just as reluctant to participate.
But this is a deplorable, short-sighted perspective.
The United States has a major interest in a stable Middle East.
This includes a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australian laws for uniform cigarette packaging enter into force
Health warnings and diseased body parts on neutral green packs that are the same for all tobacco brands
The world’s first laws for uniform cigarette and tobacco packaging have come into force in Australia, replacing brand logos and colors with neutral, olive-green lids, which are also printed with drastic images showing sick body parts and cigarette smoke-affected infants and children.
Aside from the different health warnings and pictures, the only difference between the packages in the brand names, which are printed in identical, small font, is from next Saturday.
This means that Australia is introducing the world’s most stringent regulations for tobacco packaging.
The Australian federal government wants to stop young people from smoking by removing the glamorous image of tobacco use.
Studies have shown that people who haven’t started smoking at the age of 26 are 99% unlikely to start smoking.
"You can already see in young children that they understand the message that tobacco companies are trying to promote with their brand image," said Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with the idea of a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and the changes will only have a minor impact on the profits of multinational corporations, other countries are already considering similar steps.
The tobacco lobby fought hard against the laws.
According to the law, black market trade would be favored, leading to cheaper and more accessible cigarettes.
"The laws will lead to serious, unintended consequences," said Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Chinese and Indonesian counterfeiters will offer much larger quantities of these products on the streets of Australia.
Others, on the other hand, say that the laws have boosted their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, notes that demand for cigarette cases and silicone lids to cover the unbearable packaging has risen tremendously since British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco challenged the law in the Australian Supreme Court two months ago.
Zico has sold up to 6,000 units to wholesalers and is waiting for new stocks.
This is a good business for us.
According to experts, the hook in the popularity of social media lies with the exact population group to which the plan is aimed.
A number of Australian laws have banned tobacco companies from TV advertising, banned them from acting as sports sponsors, and forced most merchants to stop selling cigarettes in stores. Now tobacco advertising has switched to the internet.
The Australian government has banned internet advertising by local companies and sites, but has no influence on international sites.
“Anyone who markets tobacco and only has a small area left to promote their products doesn’t get around the internet,” says Becky Freeman, a health care researcher at the University of Sydney.
On social media such as YouTube, Twitter, and Facebook, Freeman has noted an increase in reviews of brands written by “normal people.”
One has to ask oneself: Is this just a private person who likes Marlboro cigarettes so much that she even records a video for it - or does a marketing agency have to do with it?
British American Tobacco Australia says that instead of marketing, the industry is focusing on dealing with the new laws.
