In a constantly electrified world, it’s nice to be bored sometimes.
This Thanksgiving I unexpectedly spent five hours at the airport when our plane crashed due to mechanical problems and we had to wait for another plane.
So I had enough time to think a few things too boring.
I don't want to lie.
Waiting half a day at the airport for a flight is quite annoying – even when books, magazines, and iPhones (and of course, tax-free shopping) are available.
But more and more academics and child development experts cite boredom as something positive.
When it comes to them, it’s okay for us – and our children – to be bored occasionally.
This forces the brain to lose itself in interesting thoughts, which may promote creativity.
And because most of us are almost constantly staring at one screen or another these days, the benefits of boredom no longer benefit us.
So should we welcome boredom with open arms?
Yeah, yeah.
And no.
I will come back to that once again.
Like many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively recent phenomenon that has evolved with increasing leisure time.
But Peter Toohey, a professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of “Boredom: A Lively History” (Yale University Press, 2011) does not see it that way.
“In fact, boredom has a very long history,” he says.
The walls of Pompeii decorate a Latin graffiti about boredom that dates back to the first century.
And then there is the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After a long reading of research literature and the presentation of the idea in front of a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the conclusion that boredom can be defined as the experience of "wanting to carry out a satisfactory activity, but not being able to do so".
Boredom differs from apathy in that the person is not busy, but wants to be.
With apathy, however, there is no urge to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, is a “disruption of the attention process, coupled with a bad mood and the feeling that time is passing slowly.”
Boredom can sound like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes, although these two conditions may be related, bored individuals see the problem in their environment or the world, while depressed individuals see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we are bored, even if we just have difficulty concentrating.
In their study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention" - in English for example: "The Idle Mind: The Definition of Boredom Under the Aspect of Attention", which appeared in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science" in September, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues point to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to an article in front of a band on which a person read an article.
Some groups heard a loud TV program from the neighboring room that had nothing to do with the content; others heard it at low volume, so it was barely perceptible, while the third group did not hear these sounds at all.
The people who heard the barely audible television said they felt more bored than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, couldn't find a reason for this, and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
Trying to focus on a difficult or strenuous task can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, if you are pursuing a monotonous activity - "like the search for faulty products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract and help you not feel bored".
In fact, he says, we now know that tapping around and scribbling, often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can even fight these by keeping people more physically alert.
"Studies have shown that children who are allowed to hop around learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still," said Professor Fenske.
We all get bored at some point - my late flight, a roaring loudspeaker, a particularly tiresome movie.
But some people get bored more easily than others.
To measure these differences, researchers developed a "scale of boredom" in the 1980s.
On the scale, statements such as "Many things I have to do repeat and are monotonous" and "I have so many interests that I don't have enough time for everything."
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to get bored than girls, according to Stephen Vodanovich, professor of psychology at the University of West Florida — especially as regards the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teens are a rather relaxed bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teens and their parents with a pager seven to eight times a day.
He found that 32% of adolescents were bored at school and doing their homework, while 23% said they were bored when they were not at school.
But only 3% of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he does not know whether the percentages of boredom have increased or decreased.
However, he is sure that “youth will be perceived as particularly boring”, mainly because children and teenagers have little influence on their daily routine.
So back to my original question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases, it leads to people taking extreme physical risks and falling into gambling or drugs to alleviate them - that's what studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors are investigating the relationship between boredom and creativity. This is the opinion of Professor Vodanovich, who has been researching the subject for more than two decades.
“With boredom, the brain wants to tell you to do something else,” said Gary Marcus, professor of psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn’t always know what to do best.
When you are bored and you use that energy to play guitar and cook, you become happy.
But while television can create happiness in the short term, it will disappear in the long term.
If you give your bored child an iPad, you can stop them from getting bored, but they haven’t learned how to keep themselves entertained or to control themselves, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds: “self-control transfers from one situation to another.”
The child not only learns to talk, but also gains more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
Nor should we view them too critically.
Instead, our goal should be to feel at ease even away from constant activity and technology spills.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"It sounds like we need to be bored more often, but boredom is the tormenting, incessant desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that people are really just looking for a way to unwind and relax.
“In an environment where we’re constantly overstimulated, it’s hard to get busy once the noise has stopped.”
In Colorado, there is no clear guideline for the new marijuana law
19-year-old community college student and footballer Anthony Orozco stands trial in southeast Colorado for a crime that will soon be legal in that state: possession of a few marijuana chunks and a pipe he used to smoke them.
According to Orozco, he and some friends were driving in Lamar near the Kansas border on a September day when they were stopped.
After the police officer found marijuana in the car, Orozco was summoned for possession of drugs and drug utensils — cavalier offenses each with a $100 penalty — and received a court appointment.
"We're being treated like criminals," Orozco said.
But is he also one?
In the uncertain weeks following the state’s decision to legalize small amounts of marijuana for self-use, the response to hundreds of minor drug offenses depends less on the law than on the location.
Hundreds of lawsuits that revolve around marijuana are already being dropped here and in the state of Washington, which approved similar measures.
Police authorities will no longer prosecute adults over the age of 21 for small possessions, which will be allowed by law as soon as the new laws enter into force in the next few weeks.
But prosecutors in Colorado’s more conservative districts have announced to pursue existing marijuana offences and are still citing people in court.
At the same time, several cities, from the suburbs of Denver to the Western Mountains, are voting to prevent new, state-licensed marijuana stores from opening in their communities.
“This situation is evolving so fast that I don’t know what’s going to happen next,” said Daniel J. Oates, chief of police in Aurora, east of Denver.
And regulators in the state of Washington are also scratching their heads.
They are waiting for guidance on setting up a licensing system for the production, manufacture, distribution and sale of the drug - and have a deadline by December 1, 2013 in mind.
In Washington, it is believed that Colorado is ahead of most states when it comes to regulating marijuana, where the drug was first legalized for medical purposes and then for self-consumption.
"Colorado has a more regulated market, so the state is well-suited for orientation," said Brian E. Smith, spokesman for the Washington State Spirits Regulatory Authority.
But Smith also admits that no place or system can do more than serve in the sense of a rough guide.
“We don’t have a real precedent that we can follow,” he adds.
The Washington law, called I-502, will enter into force on December 6, also forming the end point of a gray zone in which the state licensing system does not yet exist, but ownership is legalized.
And unpleasant practical issues need to be clarified at this time – such as how to agree on the state’s requirement of “appropriate access” to licensed marijuana with the ban on cannabis stores within a 300-metre radius around schools, parks, playgrounds and childcare facilities.
"Nowhere will it be harder to find a location for a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, especially the Seattle metropolitan area," said Ben Livingston, spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a recently formed research group.
On November 21, Chief Oates sent an email to his Aurora employees stating that the prosecutor would no longer prosecute minor marijuana offenses against people over the age of 21, and that the police would not seek criminal charges for those offenses "from now on."
Chief Oates added that the police will continue to enforce urban regulations regulating medical marijuana growers and continue to prosecute drug dealers.
In Weld County in northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck holds a stricter view.
After the vote, he stated that his agency would continue to pursue cases of marijuana possession, mainly to encourage consumers to withdraw.
Currently, 119 people have to answer for possession of about 50 grams or less of marijuana in court, although many have also been charged with other offences.
"Our agency has a duty to prosecute violations that were criminal at the time of the crime," Buck said in a statement.
The reactions are even ambiguous in places such as rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the marijuana initiative.
Police in Grand Junction, the county’s largest city, no longer target adults for possession of smaller amounts.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supported this decision, but also decided not to drop all pending property proceedings.
"I don't think I'm wasting my time enforcing the law until it changes," he says.
Although 55% of Colorado voters supported the measure, it was clear from the start that it would not be easy to reconcile personal consumption of marijuana with the complexities of government and legal system.
And the contradictory reactions throughout the state fostered a profound dissension among local officials with regard to the great green experiment.
District prosecutors are a “cultural barrier,” says Sean McAllister, a Denver lawyer who represents defendants in court for marijuana offences and acts as a local spokesperson for the National Organization for Marijuana Law Reform.
"They have spent so much of their lives prosecuting people for still not being able to accept legalization," he said.
As the first states to treat smaller amounts of marijuana like alcohol, Colorado and Washington are being traded as national sample cases for the legalization of drugs.
While advocates and state officials are preparing for an era of legal sale, they are also nervously awaiting instructions from the federal government, which wants to continue to treat the sale and cultivation of marijuana as a criminal offence at the federal level.
Advocates of the legalization movement hope that the Ministry of Justice will give in.
Despite several eye-catching arrests of consumers and sellers of medical marijuana, the federal government has largely allowed the sale of medical marijuana in Colorado, Washington and 16 other states.
Kevin A. Sabet, former drug policy adviser to the Obama administration, believes that while criminal officers are unlikely to enter doors to seize smaller amounts of drugs, they are likely to resist to tolerate legal, state-regulated marijuana stores under the new legislation.
Several cities in Colorado are not even waiting for the federal authorities to act.
Even before the election day, some local municipalities approved moratoriums on new marijuana stores, although they could only open in about a year.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the west, passed a six-month ban, which is likely to be passed next week.
“We don’t want to get into a position where we’re licensing someone and then face a big problem at the federal level,” said Bob Nicholson, a member of the city council.
Our community voted against this amendment.
We are based on what the community has chosen and not on what the state has chosen.
Many questions are still open.
Petronella Wyatt: I was bullied from Oxford because I'm Tory
Not only today’s university students are being attacked for their views
It has always been my biggest dream to get a place at the University of Oxford.
Both my father and my older brother had attended the university that I once thought was the greatest temple of knowledge in the world, for a modern Greek symposium that promoted the great pillars of civilization – free thinking and tolerance.
But within two weeks of my arrival at Worscester College in the late 1980s – where I had planned to study history – I had packed my bags again and brought about the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed in tears.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard said I left because I had a problem with fellow students having sex in the next room.
Author A.N. Wilson mischievously explained that I had left the university because I was forced to drink from damaged cups.
The truth was less amusing.
I ran away.
Yes, I ran, because I suffered from systematic bullying and threats.
Not because of my rather unusual name, or because I came from a private school.
I had been harassed for only one reason - one reason that seemed all the more narrow-minded and cruel in this supposed cradle of enlightenment: my late father Woodrow Wyatt had been an important adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I was a supporter of the Conservative Party.
Why am I mentioning this right now?
Well, according to recent reports, a new generation of moderate-right students suffer similar persecution.
The organised and growing hatred of Tory students in Oxford has now developed such dimensions that a group of them last week called for the same level of equality protection that benefits gays, disabled people and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of Corpus Christi College's Junior Common Room (JCR) say they are "often actively isolated, personally attacked and declared undesirable" due to their political views.
They demand a place on the equality committee of their college to ensure that their opinions can be expressed freely.
Their situation was exacerbated by a recent BBC Two documentary about political students, "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right", which portrayed Tories as eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
Among other things, it showed graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the conservative student association of the University of Oxford, who drove in a Rolls-Royce and wore a silver suit and silver-studded walking stick.
At other universities, conservative students say they are considered “the scapegoats for introducing higher tuition.”
20-year-old Luke Black, vice president of the conservative student union at the University of Nottingham, said in a Sunday newspaper: "There is a growing leftist tendency in universities.
People think we're like the Bullingdon Club without even getting to know each other."
Samuel Roberts, 21, a history student in Corpus Christi who initiated the request for greater protection, believes such a climate is “unpleasant.” 19-year-old Stephanie Cherill, president-elect of Oxford’s conservative student association, says she has observed a growing rejection of moderate-right students among JCR members.
"This poses a threat to intellectual discourse and to the well-being of members," she says.
During my first weeks in Oxford, I belonged to such a minority.
As an incredibly shy 18-year-old, I arrived in September 1986.
The hatred of the Conservative Party had reached its peak.
Last year, the university voted not to award an honorary degree to Margaret Thatcher – a former student – due to cuts in higher education.
The atmosphere would have terrified even Stalinists.
In the first days of the first semester week, when new students get to know each other and the tutors, I got a taste of the future events.
I found that the tutors not only tolerated the mockery of Tory students, but even took part with joy.
Political issues such as the miners’ strike, privatization and the government’s rejection of sanctions against South Africa’s apartheid regime found their way into the wood-paneled rooms of the tutorial.
On my first of these events, I was supposed to translate French texts from the 18th century into English, but I had not been prepared for what was to come.
"Miss Wyatt," said tutor Harry Pitt (meanwhile deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
I stumbled.
Pitt was a little man with a face like cake dough, and quite hateful.
"Do Thatcher supporters refuse to learn French, or are they just stupid?" he asked me.
The other students laughed.
In my eyes, tears abounded.
"I suggest you take a few French lessons in your free time -- so if you're not too busy with your social activities," Pitt murmured.
I returned to my room with my head hanging.
That evening, I was sitting alone in college at dinner, when someone slightly taped me on the shoulder.
It was a second-year English student named James who introduced himself as a member of the Conservative Student Association.
"I know who you are," he said kindly.
Unfortunately, it is what it is.
Anyone suspected of being Tory will be harassed.
It's bad enough for me, but they know your father's close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's going to be worse for you.
Most Tory first semesters pretend to be Labour supporters.
In a local pub, I later tried to disguise myself.
I insisted that I did not agree with Mrs. Thatcher on all points.
This trick should prove unsuccessful.
A beginner in philosophy, politics and economics who ironically had attended Eton College, a conservative college, said to me, “You are the daughter of a fascist pig.”
You're dirty.
Other students shared his opinion.
I was perverse and dirty.
"How do Tories have sex?" one asked me.
They beat each other, right?
I felt what homosexuals must have felt before the more liberal legislation of the United States.
Would I ever manage to live a normal life at Oxford University?
Would I be able to meet like-minded people only after dark?
Should I turn to the Labour Party and suppress my natural inclinations?
The three years that lay before me stretched out before my spiritual eye into a purgatory of denial and isolation.
The only tutor to openly identify himself as Tory was Norman Stone, a professor of contemporary history who had his seat in my college.
He was hated not only for being a conservative, but also for advising Thatcher on foreign policy and writing speeches for them.
He was rarely there.
He hated the place, found it provincial and petty and rejected it for his Marxist-determinist perspective on history.
In 1997 he took up a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
"You won't be happy here," he told me.
I started commuting between Oxford and my parents’ house and found refuge with more open-minded friends and family members in the city.
I told my father that I hated Oxford and why I did it.
He seemed to be unbelieving.
During his time in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
"But it's the best place in the world," he said tiny.
They would never do such a thing, not in my city of dreaming tower peaks.
Even my communist friends always showed flawless manners.
His wet eyes were clouded.
Give the whole thing a chance.
I'm sure they're just teasing you.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by my frequent trips to London, my emotional resistance weakened.
One of my male friends, also Tory supporters, had yielded to the pressure and renounced his beliefs.
During a tutorial the following week, during which another history teacher had seriously claimed that I was "an enemy of the people", I decided to do the same.
Although I was secretly drowning in shame, I admitted that my parents had undergone a "brainwashing" and called them "old idiots."
The relief lasted only a short time.
It was my father who punched the last nail in the coffin of my Oxford career.
At that time, he wrote two columns per week in the Murdoch press.
My door was locked.
I hid in my room, and after five minutes my bunnies gave up.
When they left, I packed a suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never returned.
You are welcome to call me a weeping slutty cock.
But no 18-year-old should ever have to suffer such intimidation and malice in an educational institution.
And more tragically, it was Oxford—a university that not only produced 14 Tory prime ministers, but hiding behind an undeserved call for equality and freedom of thought to this day.
