The most difficult profession in the world: the human working animals of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and their health when they carry 70 kilos of sulphur across the steep, rocky roads.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives by extracting sulphur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, he has to climb down to the bottom of his crater every day, where the sulphur-containing gas emanating from the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulphur stones, which can weigh up to 70 kilos in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the sloping paths of stone.
While it is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to an altitude of 2,386 meters, the exhausted carriers need more than 40 minutes to climb at the turtle pace, keeping the balance and taking their steps carefully so that they do not slip and crash.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed on the steep slopes of Kawah Ijen years ago.
The Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents for every kilo of sulphur they mine.
Arriving at the top, they pave the way between the tourists they photograph like circus monkeys and walk with the tiresomely heavy baskets three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has set up a little further down at an altitude of 1850 meters
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has been exploiting the volcanic deposits since 1960 and (never to say better) its workers, for whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 eurocents) for each kilo of sulfur.
This then sells them for 10,000 rupees (83 eurocents) each to the petrochemical industry, because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used for making matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for bleaching sugar.
"Since we usually carry 70 kg, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each route," explains Anto, who normally does three routes a day.
For each race it takes three hours, after which it is completely done, but at the end of the day it has 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) combined.
What looks like a miserable wage for such an utterly inhuman effort, however, is three times what he would earn from fieldwork.
"The daily wage of miners here, where the coffee harvest pays 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros), is very high," explains the carrier, who previously worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day, and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a nearby village, for a reason as important in Indonesia as the sulphur: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her to Java to convert her to Islam".
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated because of the poisonous gases.
The 27-year-old Anto has been risking his life at Kawah Ijen for three years, whose sulphur has already left his first mark on him, even though he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated because of the toxic gases from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay for achieving his dream.
"I will work here for two more years because I want to open a store or learn Spanish or French," he promises in a more than just acceptable English.
This sympathetic and intelligent but life-punished young man might work as a tourist guide, waiter, or at the reception of a hotel, but instead he does the work of a carrier.
He shares a dirty wooden hut with other carriers and gets up every morning at two o’clock, because the sulfur also flows out at night, where its characteristic yellow color shines bluish in the dark.
Challenging the shadows, he climbs into the crater in the light of a small headlamp on his helmet, which he bought from his own money.
About 400 carriers load baskets of sulfur on their shoulders at the bottom of the crater.
Despite its large profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulphur mining to save costs, and does not provide any equipment to carriers who work on their own account and are paid by weight.
You will also not receive a share of the 30,000 rupees (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.5) supplement per camera, which the guardians of this nature park, together with the entrance fee of 15,000 rupees (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.2), charge from the tourists who come to photograph the volcano and the human carrier.
"This work is for animals and not for humans," protests Madrusin, a stubborn 42-year-old wearer who has been working at Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
He is able to carry up to 110 kg and assures that he will continue "as long as he can" because he needs the money to raise his three children aged between 10 and 18.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano was my whole life.
Even when the sulfur burns the throat and itches the eyes, when the wind suddenly turns and the miners are clamped into the thick columns that rise out of the crater, the men are so hard that no one complains about serious diseases ... of course, except for the usual breathing problems, osteoarthritis, pain in the knees and blisters on the shoulders.
With the basket on his back, Unainik is only able to carry 50 kg at the age of 53.
Every day, he and his companions break 15 tons of sulphur from the volcano, which are transported by three trucks over a goat path between the bushes to the camp in Tamansari at 18 kilometers distance.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano was my whole life," Unainik explains, opening his mouth wide, missing some teeth.
Of his five children, the eldest at the age of 30 also works as a sulphur carrier.
Time passes, but poverty persists generation after generation in one of the toughest professions in the world: that of those who work as human asses on the Kawah Ijen.
