Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
Even if these new rules could pave the way for an increase in the national birth rate, the conversations with Singaporeans working in the financial district show that they will not have a great impact.
"People are very stressed, housing and education are expensive, which is why it is postponed by many," says a young manager.
The kids can have others.
"It's important for me to have my own money and time," says another man, about twenty years old.
Men and women cite their careers, the stress and the cost of ownership and education as reasons why they cannot have children.
That’s why the Singaporeans have the last word when it comes to having children – there’s so much the government can do.
