Closing of the Unasur Summit without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6th Summit of Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, which was previously announced and theoretically to be signed by the seven governments present.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the signed document at the VI Ordinary Session of the Heads of State and Government of Unasur. Sources in the Chancellery initially announced that they would hand it over after the clausur, but then stated that it would be published at some point on the Peruvian government’s website.
When asked about the text, they stated that the content was presented to the press by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, in brief statements.
The access of journalists to information about the summit was limited at all times.
During the day, only the picture of the presidential meeting without sound was transmitted in the press room with the message "private session, limited audio".
The few information circulating among the journalists was received from the press spokesmen of some of the Unasur governments present at the meeting, but not from the Peruvian press spokesman.
The only document circulated during the day was the list of participating presidents, which caused discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media outlets demanding more information.
After that, the Peruvian presidential office sent an e-mail to the media with the “declaration” of the summit, but it was the Humala Declaration and not the official document to conclude the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South America-Arab States (ASPA), and again on this occasion, despite the press' insistent request, the so-called Declaration of Lima, which had been previously announced, was not published either.
On the official website of the ASPA, you can be sure that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed the existence of information systems for journalists, but they severely restricted access to information.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment of the Court of The Hague that settles a border conflict between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the ICC, which begins on Monday in The Hague, in the process that Lima initiated against Santiago to hear the pleadings of both sides.
"We will follow and execute the judgment on the differences we are presently bringing before this International Court of Justice," Humala said, along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has been, is and will continue to be a country that adheres to international law, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, makes agreements and submits to international courts," Piñera added, greeting Humala with a handshake in front of the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the ICC came after Colombia, following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it considered a serious mistake, filed a lawsuit against the Bogotá Agreement, in which it agreed to submit to the judgments of this International Court of Justice.
At the summit were the Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rousseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from Unasur since 2011 after the removal of its President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and concluded the summit meeting shortly after lunch in Lima.
The head of state read the final document, stating that 16 decisions were taken and the lines of action for 31 projects between South American countries were set for a total investment amount of $17 billion.
Regarding the decisions taken, he said Unasur's countries will "take significant steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we are expanding the decisions on residency rights."
He said that measures would be pushed forward to “enhance cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and organised, transnational crime, as well as measures to improve access to medicines and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and to act together and efficiently in the event of natural disasters.”
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not take on triumphant features, but should serve to expand our output and show our peoples a better future," Humala added.
"We have decided to give priority to a series of 31 emblematic projects aimed at improving spatial connections in South America and especially in rural and border areas... thus unifying our countries and opening up new economic forms," the Peruvian president said in a read-out statement.
Among these projects were five Peruvian, which were located on the transverse axis of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and two of which were intended to provide a better connection with Ecuador, although he did not give any further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the election process in this country serves for its resumption into the Union of South American nations," from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to continue to be an integrated region for prosperity and peace and with good neighbourly relations was another aspect highlighted at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before starting his participation in the regional meeting that he expected a meeting on Saturday in Mexico with his counterpart from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, to treat the maritime conflict with respect after a judgment of the ICC questioned by Bogotá.
"I may meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow," Santos said.
"We will review all these paths - they are not exclusive, and the agreement with Nicaragua also makes talks with Nicaragua necessary," he stressed.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will treat this matter as civilized and respectful as possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega would meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they intend to be present at the inauguration of the new president of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the summit, the defence ministers of the bloc also met in advance to adopt the action plan for 2013, in which dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region should be strengthened.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter country is currently excluded.
Peru holds the presidency for the time of the regional bloc.
