Cause of death due to AIDS is now a late detection
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was confirmed to be HIV-positive.
"It was like a bomb hitting," he says about the moment he was diagnosed, which the doctor "tried to mitigate without noticeable success."
He hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to learn about it; and this with such commitment that he was just celebrating his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients of the HIV unit of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), in which he came after several fights in 1994.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, which was hard to imagine in the early 1990s when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigmas.
At the time, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye “because it led to a dead end.”
AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome even with quality of life.
However, many people still come to the clinic who are unaware of their disease and in whom the virus has already done harm and exhausted their immune system, and are the victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the appearance of AIDS in the world, i.e. after the first reported cases, "the great success today means that the survival of a patient who starts treatment on time, and the survival of the general population are exactly the same," explained the head of the HIV unit of the HCG, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, saying that this information was viewed scientifically in April of this year.
Andrade Villanueva, a specialist in infectious diseases and HIV/AIDS, commented that since 2008, the scientists concluded that AIDS was not a death sentence, but that the years of survival and quality of life depended on the degree of impairment of the immune system of the people at the start of treatment, and that those who are not CD-dependent at 500 years had a higher chance of CD-dependent at 50 years.
Simply put, the above statements mean that anyone who is diagnosed with HIV-positive at the age of 25 can, in this sense, "become 75 years old without problems as long as he is under control," this expert explained.
In order to correctly classify this progress, it must be remembered that the life expectancy of Mexicans today is on average 76 years.
Even though mortality has decreased significantly in recent years (in Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS has decreased from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (annual report of ONUSIDA), it is still true that 60 percent of the patients recorded in the national database have died since the appearance of AIDS.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011 and as of May this year, there are already 187 deaths; however, it is assured that since 2005 there has been universal access to antiretroviral drugs.
So why do people still die from it?
In my opinion, the problem is not access to treatment.
This is my opinion, and so is in our hospital.
At least in the past 12 years, we have not had any medical care problems, the problem is that people are in a well-advanced state because they do not know their state of infection, i.e. in very late stages of the disease.
He makes a striking statement: "Nine out of ten patients come to us if they already have a concomitant infection. In order to influence global mortality, early diagnosis is needed, which is why all people who need it must be offered massive detection tests."
The experts and officials of the Consejo Estatal de Prevención del Sida en Jalisco (Coesida) even agree with this proposal, and also the patients like Fabrizio, who had had his test done at a private lab, and this for the only reason that it had made a friend of him who, despite his young age, was already in the AIDS-community.
Everything is different when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they'll die, and don't want to hear anything.
"If I have to die, I'd rather burst three times," they say in my case.
The change was to improve, I eat well, do sports and take the medication.
Today, his parents only know that he had cancer.
I live a normal life, just like everyone else.
"I work, do a lot, have an active but responsible sex life, I pay attention to my health and that of the other person," records Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimate details with MILENIO JALISCO to animate with his testimony those who are scared today in the context of the global AIDS day.
They should take the test if they belong to the risk group. The sooner they know if they are HIV-positive, the better, and if they already know the diagnosis, they should learn how to live responsibly like all people.
His message is a summary of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There are big holes between the health programs and the ordinary citizen, explains Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has taken care of the cause of HIV.
The most important thing is prevention.
In the designated places, "the distribution of condoms was actually increased; formerly they were handed over individually, now they are giving us packages of a hundred pieces, which is already good, but there are still people who do not have access to a condom," he said.
Among those at risk for new infections are young people.
"Why do you need them?" is a widespread mockery question from social workers, orientation staff in schools, employees in pharmacies and in the health system who do not want to expose young people, the correspondent assured.
He suggested reorienting this inefficient distribution; the condoms should be located not only behind the counter, but in outlets in public toilets of facilities that are often visited by young people.
Promiscuity should not be encouraged.
They should not be paid the beer and motel, as Governor Emilio González replied to the question of whether conservatives would be distributed under his administration.
"Sexuality doesn't look like that; it's best to bring the condoms closer to those who already engage in sexual activity," he said.
Key data of Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
The state ranks 4th in terms of new and cumulative AIDS cases, and 13th in terms of HIV.
92% of cases of infection occur via sexual intercourse, 6% via blood and 2% perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV because there are 4 or 5 people for each registered case who do not know it.
After the United States Court of Appeal has confirmed a ruling that does not recognize the restructuring of the liabilities of the Vitro Group, which has been achieved through a trade bankruptcy in Mexico, an ominous precedent is created for any national company with branches in the neighboring country that has payment problems.
So one could say that the procedures for the survival of companies that allow Mexican laws are not valid in the land of stars and stripes contrary to international agreements.
