Héctor "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
Basketball world brawler Héctor "Hetin" Reyes has been involved in basketball for more than 60 years and has travelled the world.
Few in Puerto Rico have such a large spiritual collection of the country's history of basketball as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
Before being bound to the wheelchair by a stroke in 2008, Rexes was part of this sport for 6 years, be it as a lower-class player, player of the first national league, proxy and leader in the BSN with the Vaqueros de Bayamón or president of the Basketball Association.
"All my life I have put on many hats in basketball, even several at the same time, when I was president of the BSN, chief executive of the national team and president of the association in the 1990s," Reyes recalled during a visit to Primera Hora at his home in Bayamón, where he lives with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
Basketball was my life.
Reyes does not exaggerate with this statement.
The walls of his house are almost all decorated with photos and memories of his long career and testify to them.
Bayamón in the Heart
The most emotional memories are those that remind him of his time at the Vaqueros from the mid-1950s as a player until 1982, when he celebrated his 15th anniversary as co-CEO or CEO of the club.
"These were my best years that I enjoyed the most because I was allowed to be part of eight championships of the Vaqueros since 1967, be it as managing director, co-director or coach.
There were many fulfilling years, including the five consecutive championships from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye to a championship in 1981, the year of Jerome Mincy’s debut at BSN.
From then on, "Cuco" took over Ortiz, who was a very good administrator," Reyes says.
I remember Gene Bartow, who worked as a coach here and was employed at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), saying to me, "I have a very strong and 2 m tall player.
Do you want him?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then recommended the free throw specialist Raymond Gausse, who allowed himself to be naturalized and was one of our best throwers.
I remember how he said that if Mincy had made a championship possible for Bayamon, Gausse would have made another one.
The championship of the Vaqueros with Gausse was awarded to him, but already from a distance, because he was already at the top of the association in 1988.
At that time, he preferred to enjoy his executions and those of Mincy in the national team.
I remember the first time we won against the United States at the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, in which we took fourth place, which should have been bronze, if it had not been for this Canadian referee who allowed us to repeat the last turn for the second time, Reyes said.
Was this group of the 1990 World Cup the best national team you've ever seen?
She is one of the best, as well as those who won the 2004 Olympics against the Dream Team.
But my favorite is the team of the 1991 Pan American Games in Cuba, where we won gold and offered the team of the USA a fight, as they did when they won bronze against us at the World Cup.
The team included not only Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), but also the young players (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who could not be there in 1990 due to a knee injury.
A team that was perhaps not the best in terms of personalities, but with which we won a gold medal and which gave us great joy, was that of the 1995 pre-Olympic tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourruitiner as a substitute for the suspended players due to the events at the Pan American Games in Mar del Plata, we won the gold medal against any prediction.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
This was undoubtedly Piculín Ortiz.
His numbers at the level of international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated as much at this level as Piculín.
And this without considering his career in the various leagues in which he has played.
Who was the best coach in Puerto Rico?
This is a difficult question.
We had a number of good coaches like Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
I like the work of Leo Arill.
What do you think is the best thing you've achieved in the association?
I was part of the most successful era of the national team from 1988 to 1995, which included the BSN at the beginning of the 1990s up to 17 teams in a season.
What else do you have to do?
There are things I would have introduced, such as the regionalization of the lower categories.
For example, the boys in Ponce only play in their area and only meet teams from other corners of the island in the national playoffs.
Today, the children make unnecessarily many trips and games.
At least I see the result of the prescribed training and courses for coaches, table officials and referees.
I'm proud of that.
What are you doing today?
I like to listen to music, watch videos of music of my time on YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren and occasionally go to a basketball game.
And of course I enjoy the company of my wife Isabel, who was always at my side.
